<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Ready to Cooperate with Iraq in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister
Youssef Wali said Sunday that his country is keen on offering
agricultural expertise and research results to Iraq and other Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
Wali, who is also the minister of agriculture and land
reclamation, made the remarks when meeting Iraqi Trade Minister
Mohammed Mehdi Saleh, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Wali underlined the importance of increasing agricultural trade
volume in the Arab world in view of the international economic
changes.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Wali and Saleh discussed ways of enhancing
bilateral agricultural cooperation, especially in land reclamation
and trade, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Saleh spoke highly of the quality of Egypt's agricultural
goods, hoping more trade.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's exports to Iraq reached 238 million U.S. dollars in the
first eight months of this year, leading other Arab countries in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
Saleh, who arrived here Thursday, is holding talks with
Egyptian officials on expanding bilateral cooperation and
increasing Egypt's exports to Iraq under the U.N. oil-for-food
program, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The program allows Iraq, which is under the U.N. trade embargo,
to sell a limited amount of oil to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
During Saleh's visit, the two countries will sign a number of
contracts, under which Iraq will import from Egypt steel, cement
and other building materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
