<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decision On Russian Missile Still Valid: Clerides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' President Glafcos
Clerides Sunday stressed that the decision to deploy the Russian
S-300 anti-aircraft missile is still valid, as well as the
preconditions to postpone their arrival.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at an anti-occupation gathering, Clerides said
he firmly believed that the strategy of Cypriot government on
defense and accession to European Union was correct.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the strategy was altered, the Cyprus problem
would plunge back to a prolonged stalemate.
</P>
<P>
The preconditions, he said "are either start of substantial
negotiations with prospects to achieve progress regarding the
substance of the Cyprus problem or substantial progress on
security issues, with the prospect of completing an agreement for
the gradual but eventual, complete demilitarization of Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the issue of defense has taken significant
dimensions in the past few years with the implementation of the
joint defense pact with Greece, adding that Cyprus is to continue
to strengthen its defense.
</P>
<P>
The President reassured that the aim of the Cypriot government
is "to first, find through peaceful means, a solution to the
Cyprus problem which will be fair, viable and for the benefit of
all Cypriots, and secondly, Cyprus' accession to the European
Union".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in 1974
following a failed pro-Athens coup. U.N. led efforts to reunite
Cyprus have so far yielded no results.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy S-300
anti-aircraft missiles in a bid to booster its defense, a move
rejected by Turkey which has threatened to launch preemptive
strike on the missiles if they are deployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Minister Calls for Concerted Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Health Minister
Adem Ibrahim Sunday called for national concerted efforts against
malaria in the Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
The health minister urged administrative bodies, health
institutions, governmental and non-governmental organizations and
the public to exert integrated effort to contain malaria epidemic
afflicting various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted Adem as saying that more than
70 percent of the total area of Ethiopia is suitable for mosquito
breeding.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the epidemic has worsened especially this
year due to climatic change, and failure to clear marshy areas
and spray them with anti-mosquito chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Adem stressed the need to create viable information network in
order to take strong actions against the disease.
</P>
<P>
Previous efforts to curb the pandemic went futile owing to lax
and unorganized control mechanisms, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, malaria has been rampant in
some areas of the country since this year's big rainy season
(June-October). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
