<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Tighten Regulation on Foreign Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian government will carry
out spot checks next week among foreign workers to intensify its
regulation over foreign labor market.
</P>
<P>
The spot checks is part of a campaign, launched last September,
to force illegal foreign workers to rectify their status, the
semi-official Jordan Times quoted an unnamed official as saying
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Police and Labor Ministry officials will launch a nationwide
campaign against foreign laborers working as gas station
attendants, mechanics, guards and messengers," the official said.
</P>
<P>
According to Labor Ministry figures, 110,000 illegal foreign
workers have rectified their status by obtaining valid work
permits since last September.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is also designed to return job opportunities to the
Jordanians, who are facing an unemployment rate of 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
There are 300,000 to 500,000 foreign workers in Jordan, most of
them without valid work permits.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that they have grabbed job opportunities
from the Jordanians by asking for less payments.
</P>
<P>
During the campaign, those foreign workers who are found
without valid work permits will face the danger of being fined
heavily or deported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Bank Directors Sacked for Mismanagement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Uganda has
intervened in the management of Greenland Bank and removed the
managing director and the board of directors for their improper
management of the commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Sunday by the Bank of Uganda (central bank)
said: " This measure has become necessary because, under the
present management, the commercial bank was conducting its
business in violation of the Financial Institutions Statute."
</P>
<P>
The continuation of this situation would have been detrimental
to the interests of its depositors, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
To further strengthen the financial condition and management
of Greenland Bank, the central bank has decided to take with
immediate effect the measures such as appointing new managing
director and board of directors and reducing operation hours.
</P>
<P>
Fazil Kasujja has been appointed Acting Managing Director of
the commercial bank and a new board will be appointed in
consultation with the shareholders.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the central bank will do everything
necessary to ensure that the bank continues to operate normally
and in accordance with the law and related regulations.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, President Yoweri Museveni's brother Salim Saleh
admitted under press pressure that he had used the Greenland Bank
to pay for the 51 percent shares of a Malaysian company in the
Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB).
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian company bought the shares in the UCB and
secretly transferred its shares to Saleh, the president's
security adviser and a major general.
</P>
<P>
Saleh had reportedly denied any involvement in the deal, even
before Parliament, before making a surprising admission in a
three-page statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
