<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Not to Withdraw Forces From Kuwait: British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain will not reduce
its military forces in Kuwait before Iraq really complies with the
United Nations resolutions and with what it has agreed upon, a
senior British military official said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is worrying. Saddam Hussein has got to prove to
the region and the world that it is complying with the United
Nations (resolutions) and with what was agreed upon in the middle
of November," said General Sir Charles Guthrie, British Chief of
Defense Staff.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at Kuwait's Ali Al-Salem Air Base where
400 British troops and Tornado aircraft are stationed, Guthrie
said that "we are here to see a satisfactory outcome and we have
no plans to reduce the number of aircraft here."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether his one-day visit is related to the recent
standoff between Iraq and the U.N., the British general said "No,
I'm here to see the British forces. They would not be here if
Iraq was complying."
</P>
<P>
During the recent Iraqi-U.N. standoff over weapons inspections,
Britain sided firmly with the United States in using force to
press the Iraqi regime to back down from its non-cooperation with
the U.N. special commission (UNSCOM) in charge of disarming Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On the outcome of his visit, Guthrie said his talks with
Kuwaiti government officials were "very meaningful and good."
</P>
<P>
"We discussed future plans, our position here and attitudes
towards the peoples of the region," he said. But he didn't
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Guthrie is expected to leave here later Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
