<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Clashes Continue in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Clashes between Palestinian
protesters and Israeli troops in the West Bank continued Sunday,
wounding at least two Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The clashes took place outside the Jewish settlement of Ariel
in northern West Bank when Palestinian demonstrators threw stones
at Israeli soldiers, who fired rubber bullets and tear gas in
response.
</P>
<P>
A day earlier, 27 Palestinians and three Israeli soldiers were
wounded in similar clashes throughout the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The clashes stemmed from an increasingly bitter row over
Palestinian prisoners to be released under the Wye agreement
signed October 23.
</P>
<P>
Under the Palestinian-Israeli interim agreement, Israel will
pull out its troops from another 13 percent of the West Bank while
freeing 750 Palestinian prisoners by the end of January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Israel has released 250 of them last months, but most were
criminals instead of political prisoners demanded by the Palestinian
side.
</P>
<P>
A report of Jerusalem Media and Communication Center said that
the Palestinian demonstrators set up protest tents in Gaza and
held hunger strike Sunday in support of the Palestinian prisoners
in Israeli jails, who began a hunger strike Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister of State of Prisoners Affairs Hisham
Abdul Raziq blamed Israel for the escalating clashes in the West
Bank, saying that the Israeli government failed to implement the
signed agreement accordingly.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu reiterated on
Sunday that he will not free those involved in attacks leading to
death or injury of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
He also demanded the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) stop
encouraging violent protests and clamp down on them instead.
</P>
<P>
Israel announced last Thursday to hold up the implementation of
the Wye agreement until the PNA made concessions over the prisoner
issue.
</P>
<P>
The latest woes came only six days before the U.S. President
Bill Clinton is scheduled to begin a three-day visit to Israel and
the Palestinian self-rule area to push forward the implementation of
the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Mideast peace envoy, Dennis Ross, will arrive here
Tuesday to mediate between Israel and the Palestinians over the
prisoner issue to prepare for the arrival of Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
