<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Crown Prince Meets With Texaco Chief on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabian Crown Prince
and Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz met in Riyadh
Sunday with U.S. oil giant Texaco Inc's Chief Executive Peter
Bijur on cooperation in exploring and developing the Kingdom's gas
fields.
</P>
<P>
The meeting centered on "primary offers for cooperation between
Texaco and Saudi Arabia on the exploration and investment in gas
fields," the Saudi Press Agency (SPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said the ideas on cooperation were discussed in
a way that goes in line with the Saudi policy on exploring and
investing in the gas production and distribution aimed at
generating feasible income that supports overall returns.
</P>
<P>
Saudi gas reserves are estimated at 5 trillion cubic meters,
the fifth largest global gas reserve.
</P>
<P>
Peter Bijur, who arrived in Riyadh Saturday, has come to
present his company's proposals for joint ventures to develop
the Gulf Kingdom's energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The Texaco chief's trip marks the first high-profile visit by a
leading U.S. oilman to Saudi Arabia in response to Prince
Abdullah's request for ideas on developing his country's energy
industry in a meeting with top U.S. oil executives in Washington
in September.
</P>
<P>
The rare meeting has prompted speculation that Saudi Arabia,
the world largest oil producer, could create openings in its most
treasured upstream energy industry.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports reaching here said that oil industry insiders
had said Saudi Arabia has no intention of granting foreign
companies any form of ownership in its prized upstream oil and gas
sectors.
</P>
<P>
But a Saudi oil official said Thursday that the Kingdom was
ready to consider proposals on upstream gas ventures. That
was the first clear sign that Riyadh was prepared to show
flexibility towards the upstream gas offers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
