<HEADLINE> Nigerian Warplane Crashes in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian warplane serving with
the west African peacekeeping force ECOMOG in Sierra Leone has
crashed at its base near the capital Freetown, an ECOMOG
statement said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A report from Freetown quoted the ECOMOG statement as saying
that the plane developed a technical fault on its approach run
and crashed at the Lungi International Airport Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot ejected and was unhurt, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"The accident occurred... when the Alfa Jet was returning from
a routine mission after developing a technical fault on the final
approach to landing," it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, ECOMOG has at least four Alpha Jet
ground support planes in Sierra Leone, which are used to attack
rebel positions.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led ECOMOG was sent into Sierra Leone soon after
the May 1997 coup which overthrew elected President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG forces expelled the military junta emerging after the
coup from Freetown and restored the Kabbah government in March
1998, but forces loyal to the junta are still active in the north
and east parts of the tiny west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
