<HEADLINE> Iranian Leaders for Better Ties With Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian leaders have sent
letters to their counterparts of Saudi Arabia, calling for better
relations between the two Islamic giants in the region.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister of Saudi Arabia Prince Nayef Ibn Abdul-Aziz
received Sunday a message from his Iranian counterpart Abdulwahed
Lari concerning bilateral security relations.
</P>
<P>
The letter was conveyed by Iranian ambassador in Riyadh
Mohammad Riza Nouri during a meeting with Nayef, the Saudi Press
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This message came within the context of bilateral relations
that cover political, economic, commercial, and technical spheres,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The message came just one day after Saudi Crown Prince and
Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz received a message
from Iranian President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian ambassador, who conveyed the letter, said Khatami
wished to discuss with Prince Abdullah means of developing
bilateral relations in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Saudi Arabia, once in mistrust to each other for
almost two decades, began to improve their ties since President
Khatami, a political moderate, took office in August last year.
</P>
<P>
The two countries saw a big boost since last February
when Iran's former President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani paid
a 14-day official visit to Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Hence, the two sides have exchanged a number of other
high-level visits, during which talks on ways of boosting
bilateral ties and shoring up the sagging oil prices were held.
</P>
</TEXT>
