<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Accepts Presidential Advisor's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni Sunday accepted the resignation of his brother, Salim
Saleh from the office of senior presidential advisor on defense
and security.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the President's Office said Saleh
tendered his resignation on Sunday following his Saturday
admission of impropriety in the privatization and sale of the
Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB).
</P>
<P>
In his resignation, Saleh regretted having failed to live up
to the standards expected of him as a leading cadre of the ruling
National Resistance Movement and having failed to perform duties
as a senior presidential advisor which required him to exercise
good judgement in the service of the President and of the Ugandan
people.
</P>
<P>
He said his methods in acquiring the UCB were improper and not
in line with revolutionary conduct.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said that he took personal responsibility for all his
actions and was resigning in order to enable the president to
fight improper conduct such as his and to restore the hope for
the people of Uganda in the ideals of the ruling movement.
</P>
<P>
Accepting Saleh's resignation with regret, Museveni said the
resignation was a curtain raiser in the struggle to rectify
serious mistakes and indiscipline which have been creeping into
the Movement.
</P>
<P>
He said a corrupt Movement coupled with a corrupt public
service would be disastrous for the country's recovery.
</P>
<P>
Those like Saleh, who are largely indisciplined and who do not
follow central guidance, cause problems for the Movement even if
well intentioned, the press release quoted the president as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Saleh used to be the Overseer of Defense Ministry before
taking his post as senior presidential advisor on defense and
security. He is one of few generals who contributed much to the
coming to power of the Movement.
</P>
<P>
In a three-page statement issued Saturday, Saleh admitted,
after several months of denial, that he secretly used Greenland
Bank to pay for the transference of 49 percent shares of a
Malaysian company in the UCB.  
</P>
</TEXT>
