<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League, U.N. Chiefs to Meet on Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Arab League Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said on Sunday that he would meet with U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan on the Lockerbie issue Monday in Abu Dhabi.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Abdel-Meguid
said that he would touch on the outcome of Annan's latest visit to
Libya, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting will be held on the sidelines of a summit
of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), which comprises six Arab
countries of Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the
UAE.
</P>
<P>
Both Abdel-Meguid and Annan have been invited to attend the
three-day annual summit due to open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Annan held talks Saturday with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi on
the Lockerbie crisis during a brief visit to the north African
nation which has been under U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Annan reportedly said he had fruitful and positive talks with
Gaddafi, adding that two Libyans suspected of blowing up a Pan Am
flight will be tried in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid termed Annan's visit to Libya as a positive step
towards settling the Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
But official reports, Libya disputed Annan's comment, saying
that the U.N. chief and Gaddafi did not discuss the Lockerbie
issue in their meeting.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said that he will try to unveil the reality in his
upcoming meeting with Annan.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have accused two Libyan citizens
of bombing the Pan Am 103 flight over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
1988, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The two countries succeeded in pressing the U.N. Security
Council to approve an air and arms embargo against Libya in 1992
for refusing to hand over to either of them the two suspects for
trial.
</P>
<P>
A compromise has been reached between the two western allies
and Libya that the two Libyans will be tried in the Netherlands,
as a neutral venue, by Scottish judges under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
Libya, meanwhile, is seeking guarantees that the suspects will
not be extradited to the U.S. and wants them to be imprisoned in
Libya if convicted.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League, of which Libya is a member, supports this
stance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
