<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force ECOMOG has retaken the town of Lunsar in western Sierra
Leone from the rebels, a report reaching here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Officers of the ECOMOG force were quoted as saying that the
peacekeeping troops are now in control of the town after a dawn
raid Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lunsar is a town of about 300,000 people, located on the main
road from the north of capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Relief workers reportedly said that the rebels had looted
hospitals in the town, killed about 30 residents and abducted
around 80 others.
</P>
<P>
They said that about 150,000 civilians from Lunsar and nearby
villages had fled north to the provincial capital town of Makeni.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led ECOMOG was sent into Sierra Leone soon after
the May 1997 coup that overthrew elected President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG forces expelled the military junta emerging after the
coup from Freetown and restored the Kabbah government in March
1998, but forces loyal to the junta are still active in many
parts of Sierra Leone. 
</P>
