<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Vows to Control AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
Sunday pledged to fight against AIDS which has claimed tens of
thousands of lives in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of the first Multi-Sectoral AIDS Conference in
Arusha town in north Tanzania, Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali
Juma said in a written speech that any effort to combat AIDS will
win the government's unflinching support.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president, whose speech was read on his behalf by
Deputy Minister of Health Tatu Ntimizi, said that people know of
the devastating effect of AIDS, yet the recorded cases have kept
on increasing.
</P>
<P>
The recorded AIDS cases in Tanzania rose from 44,194 in 1991
to 60,066 in 1992, a rise of almost 20,000 in just a year, he
said, noting that actual number of cases is not known in the
country because many patients do not go to hospital.
</P>
<P>
However, he said available statistics showed that since the
first AIDS case was reported in 1983, about 103,185 Tanzanians
had sought medical care although the number of AIDS cases is
believed to be around 520,000.
</P>
<P>
He noted with happiness that the epidemic is on decline in
Kagera Region in the northwest because of co-ordinated efforts.
</P>
<P>
"This is clear evidence that prevention works and we need to
make it happen in other parts of Tanzania as well," said the
vice-president.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Juma said that AIDS has
immeasurable impact on the economy due to loss in labor.
</P>
<P>
He noted that more than 86 percent of men infected with AIDS
are in the 20-29 age group while 87 percent of infected women are
aged between 15 and 44.
</P>
<P>
Juma also painted a bleak picture for children orphaned by
adults who died of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the steering committee of the conference,
Fred Mhalu, said that the gathering is an attempt to
bring together all concerned Tanzanians and their international
partners to determine why Tanzania has not been able to make
significant progress in controlling AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Mbalu said the conference is also intended to launch a
Tanzania AIDS society which aims at uniting all AIDS scientists,
researchers and experts in the control and prevention of the
deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
The conference is also attended by representatives from the
United Nations Program for HIV/AIDS and some non-governmental
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
