<HEADLINE> UK's FM Optimistic Over Annan's Lockerbie Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- United Kingdom Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said on Sunday that he is "very encouraged" by U.N.
chief Kofi Annan's talks with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi about
the Lockerbie suspects.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in an interview to the BBC television after
speaking to the United Nations Secretary-General, who held talks
with Gaddafi late on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"I think I am very encouraged by what he tells me... I think
you could sum up our mood as one of qualified optimism," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Kofi has been successful in getting across the message that we
are serious about this trial," said the foreign secretary.
</P>
<P>
Cook said it was "possible" that the two Libyans, who were
accused of bombing in December 21, 1988, could be in custody by
the 10th anniversary of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
"It is certainly a possibility,(but) it is by no means a
certainty," said he.
</P>
<P>
Cook also said that Kofi Annan had told Gaddafi the insistence
of the United States and Britain that the two men should serve
their sentences in Scotland if found guilty.
</P>
<P>
Britain and U.S are still seeking to put the two Libyans on
trial under Scottish law in Holland.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under U.N. sanctions since 1992 for its refusal
to hand over the two suspects who are accused of blowing up an
American airliner over the Scottish town of Lockerbie in 1988,
killing 270 people.  
</P>
