<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) and Egypt will sign
an agreement this month to set up a free trade zone, Egyptian
Minister of Industry and Mineral Resources Soleiman Reda said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Reda made the remarks in Abu Dhabi, where he is attending the
third Egyptian Commodity Fair, the Arabic Al Hayat reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that trade volume between the UAE and Egypt rose from
92 million U.S. dollars in 1992 to about 163 million dollars by
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Reda also said that he will discuss with UAE officials the
establishment of several major joint projects in chemical and
mineral industries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) has warned that
sagging oil prices and the financial crisis in southeast Asia will
pose further challenges to the Gulf region next year.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State for Finance and Industry Hamden Bin
Rashid al-Maktoum said such challenges entail a reform to create
further investments opportunities in the region, the Arabic Al
Hayat reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Maktoum said that member states of the Gulf Cooperation
Council will spend some 70 billion dollars on basic projects, some
of which will be financed through external loans and bonds.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The African Preferential Trade Bank has decided not
to extend more loans to Sudan due to its failure to pay its
arrears of 5.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has failed to pay back its debts despite a six-month
grace, the Arabic Alam Al Yom reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government late Saturday approved its
1999 proposed budget, totaling 2.16 billion Jordanian dinars
(about 3.051 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Deficit will be 388 million dinars (about 548 million
dollars), Finance Minister Mishail Marto told reporters late
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The budget has been submitted to the parliament for approval,
he added. 
</P>
