<HEADLINE> German Government Backs 2006 World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- German Interior Minister Otto
Schily said on Monday the new government under chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder fully supported the national football federation
(DFB)'s bid to stage the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
"The 2006 World Cup on German soil would be a fantastic event
in our football-crazy country. This first big sports event in
reunified Germany gives us a chance to present a friendly country
to sports fans all around the world," reports quoted Schily as
saying after his meeting with DFB boss Egidius Braun.
</P>
<P>
Schily and Braun agreed to set up a permanent meeting group in
January which is consist of representatives from the government,
the federal states and cities as well as the German Sports
Federation (DSB), reports said.
</P>
<P>
Germany is one of several bidders for the 2000 event which
will be given away by the world governing body FIFA in March
2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
