<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges End to Sanctions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said here on Monday that Moscow is doing its best to have
the economic sanctions against Iraq lifted.
</P>
<P>
"With the UNSCOM operation resumed, a comprehensive review of
Iraq's compliance with U.N. Security Council resolutions regarding
its disarmament should be started without delay," Ivanov said
after meeting Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has pursued the idea of such a review in a hope that it
will accelerate the lifting of the crippling oil embargo, imposed
by the U.N. Security Council following Iraq's invasion to Kuwait
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who arrived here Sunday on a four-day working visit,
promised that Baghdad would honor its commitment with regard to
Russia. He also urged Moscow to press for lifting economic
sanctions against Iraq if the Arab country obeys U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq "respects its international commitment", and assured the
Russian government that its commitment would be met, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said everything must be done to have the UNSCOM move
towards its goal. "The removal of the sanctions will facilitate
the traditional links between Russia and Iraq, particularly in the
trade and economic areas," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
"We are approaching the end of a long process which has taken
eight years and brought great suffering to the Iraqi people. It
is important now that everybody show special political
responsibility and bring this work to its logical end," Ivanov
said, reflecting on talks last week with UNSCOM Chairman Richard
Butler.
</P>
<P>
Russia "has been and will be working for stringent compliance
with all U.N. Security Council resolutions", Ivanov said.
"Compliance by Iraq with all disarmament conditions set by the
Security Council must result in the lifting of the oil embargo
against Iraq," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Aziz, Iraq expected that "a comprehensive review
of the fulfillment by Baghdad of the disarmament requirements of
the U.N. Security Council resolutions will be made next month."
</P>
<P>
Aziz is also scheduled to meet with Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov later of Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the New York Times reported on Monday
that Washington seemed ready to accept a U.N. review of Iraqi
sanctions in the hope that the review would prove again that Iraq
still has much to answer for its banned weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
"Such an outcome would strengthen the U.S. policy of keeping
sanctions in place indefinitely," the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
