<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Confident of HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, said
here Monday that Hong Kong is already on the way to recovery and
he is very confident of its future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the French Business Association Seminar held here
Monday afternoon, Tung described 1998 as an extremely difficult
year, saying that Hong Kong's economy has been greatly affected by
Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Hong Kong's property prices have come down some
55 percent. Its costs, including wages, are adjusting.
Unemployment, unfortunately, has almost doubled to 5.3 percent
lately. Hong Kong's economy this year will contract some 5 percent
overall.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, "we are becoming more competitive, and our
banking system has always been very sound and continues to be very
sound", and "the Hong Kong government has always been very
conservative in managing the balance sheet".
</P>
<P>
Tung expressed the belief that Hong Kong is in a much better
position than many of the other Asian economies, to get the
recovery going.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong is fortunate to be the gateway of the
fastest growing economy in the world.
</P>
<P>
The very first thing Hong Kong should do is therefore to
position itself properly to take advantage of the tremendous
opportunities on the mainland, under the framework of "one
country, two systems", he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should grasp the opportunity to expand further our links
and economic cooperation with the mainland," he said.
</P>
<P>
Concurrently, he said Hong Kong should also strive to keep up
its international cosmopolitan features: diversity, dynamism, and
an expanded and global horizon for the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
"We will also focus on creating an environment in which
innovation and technology can flourish" while not losing sight of
the importance of Hong Kong's traditional economic strongholds
such as financial services, tourism and a center for multinational
companies in Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
But most important of all, "we will continue to be fully
committed to sound macro economic policies, a free and open
market, a free and open economy, with no capital controls," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe strongly in upholding the rule of law here in Hong
Kong," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that Hong Kong will continue to invest heavily in
infrastructure projects such as building railways, roads as well
as in education in order to ensure its competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
