<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Young Gymnasts Take Team Title in Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- With an all-around domination,
defending champion China led all the way to savor the top team
honors in the first-day gymnastics competition Monday at the
Bangkok Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese coaches were not so care about the gold, their
seventh in a row since the 1974 Asian Games, what they were really
happy about was that their young generation of gymnasts have came
up and made a sounding debute at the international turf with a
stable performence of world class quality.
</P>
<P>
Led by 21-year-old world champion Zhang Jingjin, the Chinese
team of Huang Xu, Yang Wei, Xing Aowei, Li Xiaopeng and Zhao Sheng
collected 38.375 points from their first apparatus of the vaulting
horse, building a 0.900 cusion against closest Asian Japan.
</P>
<P>
As the competition went on, the confident Chinese young talents
were far ahead of the rest teams through the parallel bars,
horizontal bar, and the floor exercise.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Xing Aowei then turned his rotation on the
pommel horse into a showcase by scoring an event-high 9.800, which
lifting China to an unbeatble lead of 191.800 against Japan's
188.075 and South Korea's 187.625.
</P>
<P>
"They did much better than what we had expected before the
competition," said Chinese team leader Qian Kui, "Most of the kids
are on their first Asian Games and they just made much less
mistakes than what we thought. Their performence can match anyone
in the world levels."
</P>
<P>
With outstanding outs on the pommel horse, South Korea took the
silver medal by ousting Japan in the last rotation by 225.750 to
225.275.
</P>
<P>
When asked when the rest of Asia could catch up with China in
the team level, South Korean coach Lee Young-taik said through an
interpret: "Not now, the Chinese are too strong. They are far
ahead in Asia. Maybe in the future we could reach their level."
</P>
<P>
But China's head coach Huang Yubin expected tough competition
in the individual events: "Although not many teams in Asian could
build a balance team as we do, but they really have some
outstanding individul gymnasts, like Yeo Hong-chul of South Korea
and Sergey Fedorchenko of the Kazakhstan."
</P>
<P>
Yeo scored the day-high point of 9.875 on the vaulting horse
while Sergey Fedorchenko and teammate A. Dmitriyenko both marked
the second vault best of 9.850. China's best vaulter was Zhang
Jingjin with 9.725.
</P>
<P>
"We will dominate the parallel bars, floor exercises and pommel
horse while the vault, horizontal bar and rings will be shared by
South Korea, Kazakhstan, Thailand and Japan," Huang said, "the
individul events would be very tough." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
