<HEADLINE> Nakayama Voted J-League Player of Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Jubilo Iwata striker Masashi
Nakayama Monday was voted the J-League's Player of the Year at a
gala ceremony at Yokohama Arena, Kyoko reported.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old World Cup forward, who scored 36 goals in the
J-League this season before adding another in the first leg of
the championship final against Kashima Antlers, was the unanimous
choice of his fellow professionals and managers around the
league, Kyoko said.
</P>
<P>
"I'll try to use this award as a starting point for next sea
son. I know it will be harder next year, so I'll try to use my
positioning sense and movement to keep up with the youngsters,"
Nakayama was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Urawa Reds' 19-year-old midfielder Shinji Ono, meanwhile,
received the Rookie of the Year award for his attacking play for
the Saitama club and at the international level.
</P>
<P>
The Manager of the Year award went to Osvaldo Ardiles. The
Argentinian guided Shimizu S-Pulse to the runner-up spot behind
Iwata in the first stage of the J-League before announcing last
month that he would step down at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
International wing-back Naoki Soma of J-League champion
Kashima won the Fair Play award, while Scottish referee Leslie
Mottram was named the year's top official.
</P>
<P>
Players including five from Iwata, three from Kashima and one
from Yokohama Flugels were selected as the j-Leagues's Best
Eleven team.
</P>
<P>
The full team -- Goalkeeper: Seigo Narazaki (Flugels),
Defenders: Yutaka Akita, Naoki Soma (both of Antlers), Makoto
Tanaka (Jubilo), Midfielders: Shinji Ono (Reds), Daisuke Oku,
Dunga, Hiroshi Nanami, Toshiya Fujita (all of Jubilo), Forwards:
Atsushi Yanagisawa (Antlers), Nakayama (Jubilo).  
</P>
