<HEADLINE> Europe's Proportion of World Population in Sharp Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The proportion of continental
Europeans to the world population, now at one seventh, will
decline sharply by the year 2025, said the United Nations Economic
Commission for Europe (UN/ECE) here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Population decline, currently underway in Eastern Europe, is
expected to spread throughout the continent," said the ECE. "The
developing world will absorb almost all of the three billion
increase projected then for the Earth."
</P>
<P>
The UN agency cited experts as saying that the demographic
changes were largely attributable to recent declines in birth
rates and increases in death rates in parts of the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy at birth of 80 years for women and 75 years for
men is fast becoming the norm in Western Europe, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, they said, many countries in Eastern Europe
had experienced increases in mortality in the 1990s. "There, life
expectancy at birth is lower by about eight years for both men and
women." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
