<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Makes Significant Strides in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of
African Unity (OAU) said Monday that the African continent has
made significant strides in consolidating democracy, promoting
good governance and building new partnerships with the civil
societies of its members.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Victoria Oku, director of
Administration of the OAU, on behalf of OAU Secretary General, at
the 4-day Second Conference on Democracy, Civil Society and
Governance in Africa, which was opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
She noted that many African countries have embarked upon a
process of political transition with the objective of
institutionalizing democratic practices.
</P>
<P>
"In 1996, 18 states in Africa conducted multi-party elections
and in 1997, over 10 countries were involved in multi-party
elections," she said, adding that the OAU has so far taken part
in the observation of some 60 presidential and legislative
elections at the invitation of the countries concerned.
</P>
<P>
Lalla ben Barka, depute executive secretary of the United
Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), said at the meeting
that Africa still "face certain challenges that make the
transition to peaceful, democratic and pluralist system of
governance very difficult," as the continent continues to be
traumatized by wars and conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Referring to conflicts in the Horn of Africa, the Great Lakes
region, Southern Africa and West Africa, Barka said "these
conflicts have had and continue to have extremely adverse effect
on the evolution and consolidation of democracy in the
continent."
</P>
<P>
"Without peace and stability no amount of effort will secure
enduring democracy or lasting improvement in governance," she
noted.
</P>
<P>
During the 4-day meeting, participants from 25 African
countries will assess and evaluate the progress of democracy and
good governance in "early starters" countries, such as Cote
d'Ivoire, Benin, Ghana, Kenya, Tanzania, Zambia, Zimbabwe,
Botswana and Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
The First Conference on Democracy, Civil Society and
Governance in Africa was held in December 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
