<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Support S.Korea's DPRK Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Monday appealed to
the United States to support its policy of engaging the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
South Korean Foreign Affairs and Trade Minister Hong Soon-young
made the appeal when he met with visiting U.S. policy coordinator
on the DPRK William Perry.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Hong explained to Perry that the engagement
policy was the most realistic and effective policy under the
current circumstances, said a South Korean official.
</P>
<P>
"If we continue to push for the (engagement) policy on a long
and mid-term perspective, it will help improve South-North Korean
relations," Hong was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Perry, who arrived here Sunday, is empowered to gather
first-hand material of how South Korea views the suspected DPRK
underground nuclear site in Kumchangni, some 40 kilometers
northwest of Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Hong told Perry, who also discussed the Kumchangni issue with
President Kim Dae-jung Monday, that the issue should be carefully
dealt with as there was no "conclusive evidence" that it was
nuclear-related.
</P>
<P>
Perry is due to meet South Korean Defense Minister Chun
Yong-taek before leaving for a visit to China Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Perry's visit coincided with the nuclear talks held between
U.S. special envoy Charles Kartman and DPRK Deputy Foreign
Minister Kim Gye-kwan in Washington Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington talks, followed by the talks in New York Friday
and Saturday, are the third round since Kartman and Kim held the
first meeting in Pyongyang last month.
</P>
<P>
During the previous talks, Washington demanded that Pyongyang
allow U.S. access to the Kumchangni site to clear away the
suspicion that the site is nuclear related.
</P>
<P>
However, Pyongyang, which initially refused the U.S. offer by
saying it was "insulting", now insists that Washington pay 300
million U.S. dollars in return for the inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
