<HEADLINE> Mongolia to Expand Financial System Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's central bank has
decided that expanding the reform of financial system and
maintaining the stability of the Mongolian currency, the togrog,
will be the top priorities of the government financial policies
next year, Mongolbank Governor J. Unenbat said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Unenbat said that his country would further improve its
financial regulations and strengthen surveillance by the central
bank on bank activities.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Mongolia would strive to keep the inflation
rate to within 15 percent and realize a net foreign reserve of 90
million U.S. dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hit by the Asian financial turmoil, Mongolia faces a tougher
financial situation this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first ten months, the country's budget deficit stood at
69.3 billion togrogs (770 million dollars) while the exchange rate
against the U.S. dollar dropped from 820 togrogs to 900 togrogs.
</P>
