<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Teenager Defies Odds to Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese teenage Yasuko Tajima
overhauled China's world record holder Chen Yan to wrench a gold
in the women's 400m individual medley here on Monday when China
and Japan split all five golds at stake on the first-day of
swimming competition at the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
The gold has been considered as a certainty for China who
boasts a "double safe", namely world record holder and world
champion Chen Yan and Wu Yanyan, world recorder in women's 200m
individual medley.
</P>
<P>
But Tajima proved it was not. The 17-year-old teenager raced
to a one-length lead in the first butterfly leg and built it up to
over four seconds after the backstroke leg, leaving Chen and Wu
far behind.
</P>
<P>
She then gave her rivals no chance, powering home in 4 minutes
and 39.92 seconds. Wu came in second in 4:46.74, with Chen third
in 4:47.34, well below her own world record of 4:34.79.
</P>
<P>
But Tajima was not satisfied with her triumph. She said: "That
wa not a real victory, because this was not a close race against
the Chinese and I lost concentration in the end."
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to beat them at the 2000 Sydney Olympics," the
Japanese prodigy said with confidence.
</P>
<P>
Tajima's performance surprised her Chinese opponents. "This is
Tajima's personal best this year," said Chinese coach Wu Jicai,
"Chen and Wu had overtrained the last whole year to prepare for
the Chinese Eighth National Games and the World Championships, and
they are now in low forms."
</P>
<P>
Chen set the new world record of women's 400m individual medley
in the Chinese Eighth National Games while 20-year-old Wu rewrote
the world mark of women's 200m individual medley with a winning
time of 2:09.72 in the domestic games.
</P>
<P>
Those two sensations continued their winning momentum in the
World Championships in January when Chen won in 400m freestyle and
individual medley and Wu claimed the 200m individual medley in
Perth, Australia.
</P>
<P>
"Chen was hampered by a waist injury," said Chinese swimming
head coach Zhang Xiong, "The bed pad in the Village is too soft
and slowed her speed to convalesce."
</P>
<P>
The gold of men's 200m freestyle also went to Japan when Yosuke
Ichikawa clocked a winning time of 1:52.46 in the finals. Torlarp
Sethsothorn of Thailand finished second in 1:52.53. Ichikawa's
teammate Shusuke Ito won the bronze in 1:52.81.
</P>
<P>
All other three golds were clinched by Chinese swimmers.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 100m freestyle finals, 20-year-old defending
champion Shan Ying, who qualified as the last-but-one, led
throughout the whole course, touching home in 56.20 seconds to win
the gold.
</P>
<P>
Her teammate Chao Na, who swam shoulder to shoulder with Shan
in the first 50 meters, clocked 56.39 to settle equally with
Japan's Sumika Minamoto for the silver.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Zeng Qiliang, staved off a strong challenge
from defending champion Japanese Akira Hayashi to finish first in
the men's 100m breaststroke in 1:02.32. Hayashi managed the
silver in 1:02.55. The bronze went to Malaysia's Elvin Chia, who
was timed 1:03.09.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women swimmers proved they were still invincible in
4x200m freestyle relay race in Asia when they clocked 8:08.00 to
retain the gold by a big margin. Japan followed in second in
8:12.06. Chinese Taipei overtook South Korea in the last leg to
win the bronze.  
</P>
</TEXT>
