<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Study of Chinese River Dolphin under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese have begun a major
survey along the Yangtze river on the white flag dolphin, which is
believed to be on the verge of extinction.
</P>
<P>
Wildlife specialists in 19 ships with special equipment are
cruising up and down on the middle and lower reaches of the
Yangtze to determine the exact number of the mammals, what their
environment is, and their prospects for the future.
</P>
<P>
The white flag dolphin is unique to China. Official statistics
put its numbers at fewer than 100, much fewer than the more
publicized giant panda. In a similar study last year, wildlife
specialists spotted only 21 dolphins.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Agriculture's Fishing Bureau, the
sponsor of the study, the central government will work out a
comprehensive plan based on the results of the study to ensure the
survival of the animal.
</P>
<P>
Ecological data on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze
produced by the December 4-9 study, will be published with an
environmental report on the Three Gorges Dam early next year.
</P>
<P>
Foggy and windy weather along the river has prevented the
scientists from finding very much so far.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
