<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Meets Setbacks in Asian Games (Day Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- China suffered humiliating
defeats in swimming and shooting although it wrapped up the Day
Two Asian Games action with six gold medals on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Japan, who claimed to shake China's dominance in swimming
before the competition began, snatched two gold medals in the pool
while China landed three.
</P>
<P>
Unfancied Yasuko Tajima of Japan beat China's world individual
medley champions Wu Yanyan and Chen Yan in the women's 400m medley
final. Her clocking of 4:39.92 was 6.82 seconds ahead of 200m
world champion Wu and 7.40 faster than Chen, world record holder
for the event.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Zhang Xiong said Chen had been troubled by
back muscle strain and wasn't in her top form.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Yosuke Ichikawa won the men's 200m freestyle event
in a time of 1:52.46, beating Thailand's Torlarp Sethsothorn
into second place by 0.07 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Former world champion Shan Ying of China snatched the first
swimming title in the women's 100m freestyle final, clocking 56:20
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Chao Na and Japanese Sumika Minamoto shared second
place with an indentical time of 56.39.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100m breaststroke gold went to Chinese Zeng
Qiliang, who splashed home first in 1:02.32, edging Japanese
Akira Hayashi into second.
</P>
<P>
China grabbed the day's last swimming gold by clocking 8:08:00
in the 4x200m freestyle, nipping Japan by 4:06 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"Japanese performance today was not bad," said Japanese head
coach Tsuyoshi Aoki.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Zhang Xiong echoed his counterpart's comment
by saying "it's not bad for China." But their expressions told the
difference.
</P>
<P>
Zhang posed a serious face after the competitions while the
Japanese head coach was all smiles.
</P>
<P>
Chinese sharpshooters, who aim for half of the shooting titles
in the Asian Games, didn't win a single gold on Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea,
Kazakhstan and Thailand split the four golds at stake on the
opening day of shooting.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's Vladimir Guchsha won his first major title in the
men's free pistol, beating former Olympic champion Wang Yifu of
China into second place.
</P>
<P>
China found some solace in the women's weightlifting as Liu
Xiuhua snatched a new world record of 83.5kg en route to winning
the women's 48kg division. The previous snatch mark of 83kg was
set by Li Zhuo of China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Lan Shizhang landed the day's only other lifting title
in the men's 56kg class after totaling 275kg.
</P>
<P>
Japan walked away with all three golds in the men's judo
finals while South Korea swept all four taekwondo titles.
</P>
<P>
Japan topped the medal tally with seven golds, five silvers
and four bronzes, followed by China in 6-6-5 record and South
Korea in 5-2-1. Thailand placed fourth in 2-2-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
