<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam-ASEAN Trade Near 5.3B Dollars in 10 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Trade value of Vietnam with the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) members reached
nearly 5.3 billion U.S. dollars in the first ten months of this
year, according to Vietnam News Agency (VNA) Monday.
</P>
<P>
During this period, Vietnam earned 1.8 billion dollars from
exports to other ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
Trade with other ASEAN countries now accounts for about 30
percent of Vietnam's total foreign trade value.
</P>
<P>
Of the ASEAN countries, Singapore is Vietnam's largest trade
partner with annual two-way trade value rising to more than 3
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singapore imports crude oil, coffee, seafood, textiles and
garments, and footwear from Vietnam, while selling motorbike and
car accessories, fertilizers, oil and petrol, steel and iron to
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In the first ten months of 1998, Vietnam earned more than 1
billion U.S. dollars from exports to Singapore and imported goods
worth nearly 2.3 billion dollars from this country alone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vietnam's trade with Thailand stood at 600 million
dollars, with the Philippines nearly 400 million dollars, with
Malaysia nearly 270 million dollars, and with Laos more than 85
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, trade with ASEAN countries has been hindered by many
difficulties since mid-1997 due to the devaluation of the
currencies of many ASEAN countries, according to Vietnam's
Ministry of Trade.
</P>
<P>
Many main export items of Vietnam lose their competitive edge
compared with the same kinds produced by other ASEAN members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
