<HEADLINE> Singapore in Joint Navy Exercises With Brunei, Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Singapore
Navy is now engaged in separate joint exercises with its Brunei
and Swedish counterparts, according to announcements of the
Singapore Ministry of Defense.
</P>
<P>
The RSN and the Royal Brunei Navy started Monday an annual
scenario gaming exercises, codenamed Exercise PELICAN, at Brunei
Naval Base's Tactical Training Center. The exercise will end on
December 12.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said Exercise PELICAN is in a "high intensity"
combat environment comprising airborne, surface and submarine
threats.
</P>
<P>
In the exercise, the Brunei navy is represented by command
teams from three missile gunboats while the Singapore navy is
represented by command teams from a missile corvette, a missile
gunboat, a patrol vessel and a f-50 maritime patrol aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also said that Exercise PELICAN, the 20th in
series, aims to enhance the professional cooperation and
understanding between the two navies which interact regularly in
other courses, training programs and professional exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to an earlier announcement by the
ministry, a mine-counter-measure exchange program, codenamed LEJON
SINGA, is going on between the Singapore navy and the Royal
Swedish Navy. LEJON SINGA started last Friday and will end
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
For LEJON SINGA which is the third of an annual exchange
program, the Singapore navy has deployed two mine-counter-measure
vessels and an support vessel while the Swedish navy has sent six
officers to participate in the command post planning on board the
ships.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore navy and the Swedish navy cooperate with each
other in the training of naval units and often share their
expertise in naval operations. In addition to the
mine-counter-measure exchange program, the Swedish navy also helps
the Singapore navy in submarine training of officers and
specialists and participates in the Singapore navy's Midshipmen
Sea Training Deployment and Naval Junior Officers' Course.
</P>
</TEXT>
