<HEADLINE> Thai Govt to Hold Public Hearing on Bills Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will soon
hold a public hearing on 11 contentious bills designed to restore
Thailand's economy, Thai News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted government spokesman Akapol Sorasuchart as
saying that representatives from relevant parties would be invited
to the hearing to be held in the Government House Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The public hearing is the government's attempt to appease
public criticism and strong opposition from both the opponents and
senators who said the bills would blaze the way for foreigners to
acquire greater local assets.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai will open and chair the hearing,
and Finance Minister Tarin Nimmanhaeminda will lead concerned
ministers to explain the bills and the need for the bills to the
public.
</P>
<P>
The hearing will be broadcast on Channel 9 and Channel 11 as
well as on radio stations. Questions from the audiences are
welcome.
</P>
<P>
Akapol said findings and the views expressed at the hearing
would be compiled to supplement the government's further
consideration on whether the amendment bills would go ahead.
</P>
<P>
"What all we want to do is to clarify the public understanding
over the contentious bills on how they are vital to bringing the
country's economy back on track and not at the expenses of the
Thais," he said. 
</P>
