<HEADLINE> U.S. Farmers Block Border Crossings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. farmers shut down several
border crossings between Canada and three midwest U.S. states
Sunday to protest against what they say are unfair Canadian
trading practices, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of American farmers from Minnesota, North Dakota and
Montana closed several entry points to Canadian trucks for three
hours.
</P>
<P>
"All of us here are trying to play by the rules," said one man,
who joined about 40 other farmers at Pembina, North Dakota, to
turn away Canadian trucks from the third-busiest
Canada-U.S. border point.
</P>
<P>
The protesters alleged the Canadian Wheat Board was dumping
cheap grain into the United States, driving down American prices
and threatening the local economy.
</P>
<P>
In fact, a new bilateral trade agreement, announced Friday, has
been hailed by the governors of several grain-belt states and by
major farm groups such as American Farm Bureau Federation. But the
protesting farmers say the deal doesn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
They demanded a fixed currency exchange rate between the two
nations and an immediate moratorium on all Canadian agricultural
products entering the United States.
</P>
<P>
Farm trade between the U.S. and Canada is worth about 21
billion Canadian dollars (13.65 billion U.S.dollars) a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
