<HEADLINE> Natural Disasters Kill 401 South Koreans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Natural disasters killed 401
people and caused 1.5 trillion won (1.3 billion U.S. dollars)
worth of damage in South Korea in the year to October, the South
Korean Natural Disaster Prevention Countermeasures Headquarters
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Another 237 people were wounded and 180,809 displaced by the
catastrophes, such as floods and typhoons, according to the
organization.
</P>
<P>
About 90,500 buildings and 151,256 hectares of farm lands were
submerged, and 2,365 roads and bridges were damaged or destroyed
by floods.
</P>
<P>
Kyonggi Province with property damage reaching 460 billion won
(0.4 billion dollars) was hardest hit, followed by North Kyongsang
Province with 420 billion won, North Chungchong with 145.8 billion
won, South Kyongsang Provinces at 141 billion won, and Seoul with
51.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
After the disasters, the organization collected 66.6 billion
won (60 million dollars) through various fund-raising campaigns
for victims in disaster-hit areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
