<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Leaders Arrive in UAE for summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Abu Dhabi, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the member states of
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) arrived here Monday for their
annual summit designed to boosting regional cooperation in various
fields.
</P>
<P>
President of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan
al-Nahyan greeted the leaders of the other five GCC countries upon
their arrival at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa al-Thani said at the airport
that the Arab nation faces a number of challenges and the Gulf leaders
will discuss how to enhance unity in greeting the challenges.
</P>
<P>
He said the GCC leaders will review how to enhance their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah said
that the summit will be a chance for the Gulf leaders to discuss
ways to ensure the stability and prosperity in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Leaders will be taking part in the three-day summit due to
start Monday evening at the Abu Dhabi Intercontinental hotel, which
will allow them to take stock of the recent developments in the region
and the world and formulate a unified stand for the bloc.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the summit will be U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
chief of Arab League Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguild, Secretary General of
Organization of the Islamic Conference Ezzidine Laraki and other
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The summit is the fourth to be held in the UAE since the founding
of the regional political, economic and defense alliance in 1981, which
groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of the Gulf summit, the UAE has taken very intensive security
measures around the Intercontinetal hotel where the summit will be
held and other hotels where the delegations stay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Pansold Convicted and Fined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Former club's head doctor Bernd
Pansold was convicted and fined by a Berlin court Monday, putting
former East Germany's doping policy under the spotlight came to
an end.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, Pansold, the last of six officials of
the swimming section of Berlin club SC Dynamo to be judged, was
fined a 14,400 marks (8,600 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Like the others on the first trial, the 56-year-old stood
accused of having caused bodily harm to female swimmers by giving
them banned drugs in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Two of those accused, doctor Dieter Binus and coach Rolf
Glaeser, had earlier been convicted by the court and fined.
</P>
<P>
The other three -- coaches Volker Frischke, Dieter Krause and
Dieter Lindemann -- saw the cases against them dropped after
paying fines.
</P>
<P>
Under German law a court can decide to drop charges in return
for payment of a fine if it believes the case does not justify
the time and resources needed to bring it to a verdict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
