<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three People Executed In Guangdong For Drug Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese convicted of drug
smuggling were executed today by a local court in the city of
Shanwei in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Eleven other Chinese involved in the same case were given the
death penalty with a two-year reprieve, life imprisonment, or a
lesser term of imprisonment, according to a Supreme People's Court
announcement today.
</P>
<P>
On April 22, the three men, Huang Shang, Xu Tao, and Lin He,
were caught smuggling 219 boxes of drugs, weighing a total of
4,354 kg, by marine police patroling close to Shanwei.
</P>
<P>
The Intermediate People's Court of Shanwei made the first
judgement on September 6 and later the Higher People's Court of
Guangdong rejected the defendants' appeal and upheld the
intermediate court's decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
