<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Doubts Netanyahu's Sincerity on Wye Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat expressed on Monday his
doubts over the sincerity of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to implement the latest peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Israeli opposition Meretz Party leader
Yossi Sarid in Gaza, Arafat noted that Netanyahu tries to avoid
carrying out the terms of the land-for-security accord on which he
signed.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached on October 23, Israel would hand
over 13 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians during the
second redeployment, in return for tougher measures by the PNA
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu warned last Thursday that Israel would suspend
the troop pullback until the PNA made concessions over the issues
such as the release of Palestinian prisoners and the Palestinian
statehood.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has on several occasions reaffirmed that he would
declare an independent Palestinian state next May when the Oslo
accord expires, but this was bluntly rejected by Israel.
</P>
<P>
On Monday the Palestinians continued demonstrations in the West
Bank in protest of the Israeli government's refusal to release the
Palestinian prisoners charged with anti-Israel activities.
</P>
<P>
Of the 750 Palestinian prisoners that Israeli agreed to release
as stipulated in the peace deal, 250 were freed last month, but most
of them were common criminal, rather than political detainees.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Palestinians gathered at a road crossing near the
West Bank town of Ramallah and burned tires. But no clashes
between the demonstrators and Israeli troops were reported.
</P>
<P>
The latest disputes between Israel and the Palestinians over
the implementation of the peace agreement came on the eve of a
tour by the United States President Bill Clinton in the region.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to arrive here Saturday night for a
three-day visit in Israel and the Palestinian-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli official told Israel radio Monday that a three-way
meeting between Clinton, Netanyahu and Arafat could take place on
Monday in the Erez checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu noted on Sunday that Clinton's visit will be
valued only if he stresses the fulfillment of the Palestinian
commitment under the agreement during his tour.
</P>
<P>
Some Israeli officials now expressed the fear that that Clinton
setting foot on the soil under Palestinian self rule would give a
boost to Palestinians' desire for statehood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
