<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Clean Sweeps Three Golds in Judo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese made a clean sweep of
all three medals offered on the first day of judo competition in
the Asian Games here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tokuno Kazuhiko, who won the World Cup title in Minsk, Belarus
in November, beat Yang Bo of China in the men's 60-kilogram
category to win the gold.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old, a policeman at home, counted on his expierence
and explosive power to overwhelm Yang, who looked a bit nervous
most of the time.
</P>
<P>
"This is my first Asian Games victory and I hope I can win in
next year's world championships," said Tokumo, who jumped to fame
by winning the gold of the same class in the East Asian Games at
Pusan, South Korea in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Larpanant Thiti shared the third place with South
Korea's Kyun Seung-Hoon before a boisterous home crowd.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 66-kg category, Nakamura Yukimasa disposed off
Ivan Beglayev of Kazakhstan for the win. The third place went to
Mongolia's U. Erdenebaatar and Iran's Arash Miresmaeili.
</P>
<P>
Makabe Tomoe completed Japan's clean sweep in the women's 48-kg
class by beating DPR Korea's Cha Hyon-Hyang with an unanimous
decision.
</P>
<P>
Three referees also ruled Tomoe the winner after neither of the
two finalists could score during the five-minute duel.
</P>
<P>
"I felt a little stressed in the first match against Yu
Shu-Chen of Chinese Taipei, but I got completely relaxed from the
second on," the 24-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
Gao Lijian of China failed cross the second-round hurdle when
she dropped to DPR Korea's Cha Hyon-Hyang, whom she defeated in an
international judo competition in northeast China's Changchun in
September.
</P>
<P>
Gao, 18, displayed spectacluar form after the loss and scored
two successive victory to finish joint third with Cha.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian Games was even more competitive than the world
championships and Olympic Games since Japan and South Korea were
the two of the most powerful nations of the sport, " said Liu
Yuqi, manager of the Chinese national team.
</P>
<P>
But Yang's coach Liu Wugong said it's the starting point for
the two Chinese judocas because they are still very young.
</P>
<P>
"Yang is only 19 and Gao 18, they will be the medal hopefuls in
the Sydney Olympic Games," Liu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
