<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes 1.5 Tonnes of Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced on Monday
that nearly 1,500 kilograms of narcotics were seized from Afghan
traffickers in the northeastern Khorasan province in the past
two days.
</P>
<P>
The official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) quoted a
report from the provincial security forces as saying that the
drugs included 106 kilograms of heroin and 1386 kilograms of
opium.
</P>
<P>
During armed clashes with traffickers in several parts of the
province, the Iranian security forces killed seven traffickers
and arrested seven others, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Iran launched strict campaigns against drug trafficking in 1989
after the Iranian Majlis passed an anti-drug law, which allows
death punishment on those caught with more than 30 grams of heroin
or five kilograms of opium.
</P>
<P>
Despite of an increase in the amount of confiscated drugs
during recent years, drug trafficking remains as a serious problem
for Iran as it is one of the best transit route for smugglers to
carry drugs from Afghanistan to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
