<HEADLINE> South China Island City Welcoming Hong Kong Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Wang Faren, the mayor of Haikou,
capital of China's island province of Hainan, said today that
investment from Hong Kong is warmly welcomed and that the city
government will try its best to serve the investors.
</P>
<P>
The mayor told members of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) living in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) that his tropical city has a modern
traffic network and an urban afforestation rate of 40 percent, and
it ranks first in among the provincial capitals in the country in
telephone coverage.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, 49.79 billion yuan (6 billion US dollars)
was spent on the city's infrastructure, 25.8 times the total spent
in the sector from 1949 to 1988, the year Hainan became a
province, according to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
The province has approved 6,019 overseas-funded projects, worth
4 billion U.S. dollars, the majority of that coming from Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the city had over 780 overseas-funded
companies with annual sales of more than 4 billion yuan (483
million US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Takes Measures to Curb Non-Performing Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tarin told the Foreign Bankers' Association in Thailand that
the Finance Ministry planned to increase the role of the Bank of
Thailand in supervising corporate debt restructuring.
</P>
<P>
As a measure to achieve this goal, banking regulators will
meet commercial bankers Tuesday to discuss new measures to curb
non-performing loans, Tarin said.
</P>
<P>
Loans in arears for up to three months currently made up
one-third of all non-performing loans in the banking system.
Non-performing loans in Thailand currently stand at about 20
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Regulators will take "a more aggressive role" in pressing
creditors to agree to a solution, Tarin said.
</P>
<P>
"One possibility was to pass deals in dispute among creditors
involving corporate debt restructuring out of court," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tarin said that although the overall economy has shown
improvements, the government must still press forward with
measures such as financial reforms, increased public spending to
boost local demand.
</P>
<P>
He predicted the domestic economy will see a positive growth in
the first quarter of next year, if all policies were undertaken.
</P>
</TEXT>
