<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defecting Khmer Rouge Commanders Arrive in Phnom Penh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PNOM PENH, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A group of Khmer Rouge
commanders who surrendered to the Royal Government of Cambodia
last Friday arrived here Monday from the Thai-Cambodia border at
Preah Vihear and Samlot.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held for them by the Information
Ministry, they said their defection to the government means
Cambodia's 20-year civil war has finally ended. "We want to have
peace and stability in our country. Fellow countrymen must stop
fighting with each other," they said.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Khmer Rouge troops under Ta Mok agreed to
unconditional defection last Friday following more than four hours
of negotiation in Preah Vihear with Meas Sophea, the Royal
Cambodian Armed Forces (RCAF)'s deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
Among the defecting commanders are Ta Mok's top military and
policy aides, including Pol Non, Dul Saroeun, Ta Them, Khem Nguon
and Nuon Nou.
</P>
<P>
Also, Iem Phan and Ta Mok's son-in-law Ta Muth, who have been
commanding troops in Samlot district in Battambang for the last 17
months, will defect with their troops, according to military
officials.
</P>
<P>
Military analysts said various factors contributed to the
timing of the defection, such as the formation of the new
coalition government and its recognition by the international
community as well as the capitulation of most of the resistance
forces loyal to Prince Ranariddh and so on.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen last Saturday expressed his welcome to
the defectors. He said, "at this new historical stage, your
actions have reflected your good will in strengthening peace and
national unification."
</P>
<P>
But Hun Sen reiterated Monday when he met with Vietnamese
Ambassador to Cambodia Nguyen Duy Hung that three Khmer Rouge top
hard-liners Ta Mok, Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan must be tried. The
tribunal to try them should take place in Cambodia with the help
of the international community, and they must be tried in
accordance with Cambodia's law.
</P>
<P>
"Recently, the recapture of rebel forces-controlled areas along
the Thai-Cambodian border has been going on smoothly. With the
defection, Ta Mok, Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan are further
isolated," said Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
"Now we can say the danger of the return of the Khmer Rouge has
totally disappeared. This is very important to the security and
development of the country. It will also improve the investment
and tourism environment," the prime minister added.
</P>
<P>
But the defectors declined to offer the whereabouts of Ta Mok
and any information about the three top Khmer Rouge leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
