<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Abu Dhabi, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The 19th summit of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) opened here Monday evening with the aim of
cementing regional cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The GCC was born in Abu Dhabi in May 1981 when the leaders of
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates held their first summit.
</P>
<P>
The six Arab gulf states formed the alliance designed to enhance
coordination, cooperation and unification of the member states in all
fields in a strategic and oil-rich region.
</P>
<P>
The GCC has three main structures, namely, the Supreme Council, the
Ministerial Council and the Secretarial General based in Riyadh, Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the group meet once a year to develop their plans for
collective security and economic unity.
</P>
<P>
One of the main GCC targets is to establish a common market,
unifying custom duties, industrial policies and investment laws and
setting up a unified currency.
</P>
<P>
The six countries produce nearly 13.5 million barrels of oil each
day, accounting for one fifth of the world's total of oil production.
Their oil reserves, which are estimated at 465 billion barrels,
account for 45 percent of the total global oil resources.
</P>
<P>
The GCC oil producers, whose economy depends heavily on oil
earnings, have taken a hard hit in the current oil price slump
resulting from oversupply and flagging demand. Eitem

NNNN
21:33 21:33 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
