<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sexual Diseases Third Most Common Infectious Disease In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Sexually transmitted diseases
(STDs), which had practically disappeared from China a few decades
ago are now just behind dysentery and hepatitis as the most common
infectious diseases, according to the National STD Control Center
(NSCC).
</P>
<P>
China reported 461,510 cases of STDs last year, a rise of 15.8
percent from 1996, an incidence of 37 persons per 100,000. But,
the real number may be five to ten times the reported figure, the
Ministry of Health (MOH) says. A new MOH document says that most
cases are not reported because patients often go to private or
unauthorized clinics to keep the matter quiet.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the cases involved extra-marital sex, but
20 percent of the cases occur in married couples. People in
well-developed areas and cities run a higher risk of getting the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the cases reported are in Guangdong, Jiangsu,
Zhejiang, and Sichuan provinces and in the city of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Although gonorrhea is the leading STD in China, syphilis is
increasing at a rate of 62 percent every year, and an increasing
number of new-born babies were STD victims last year. The
incidence of STDs among children less than a month old rose by 70
percent last year from 1996. Doctors fear that the situation may
worsen if pre-marital health checks are not tightened.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean President to Discipline Military Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung will soon discipline military leaders responsible for
recent accidents in which 11 soldiers were killed, presidential
spokesman Park Jie-won said Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said, "Investigations of the accidents
are still under way and it is still too early to talk about the
scope and timing of disciplinary action. The president did not
make concrete comments on the issue."
</P>
<P>
When asked whether Defense Minister Chun Yong-taek will be
sacked, the spokesman did not give a clear-cut reply.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's remarks were seen as an apparent response to
pressures from the public and the opposition Grand National Party
(GNP)to sack the defense minister in the wake of the recent
accidents.
</P>
<P>
"The accidents, which involve the army, air force and navy, are
the results of lax discipline and the rock-bottom state of
morale," said Ahn Taik-soo of the GNP.
</P>
<P>
Ahn said President Kim's pursuit of an engagement policy
toward the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) is to
blame for the loose discipline and low morale among servicemen.
</P>
<P>
"The sunshine policy caused confusion over just who our chief
enemy is and this resulted in lax discipline and low morale," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Public trust in the military would decrease if no one,
including the defense minister, assumed responsibility, the GNP
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Last week's military accidents came on the heels of a failure
by the South Korean military to capture an alleged DPRK spy boat
which was found in the South's west coast waters last month.
</P>
<P>
In the past four weeks, the 11 soldiers, mostly with the army,
were either killed by tanks or in explosions or car crashes.
</P>
<P>
In an unprecedented accident, an air force anti-aircraft
missile was accidentally launched last Friday, injuring
three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
