<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Aims for Public Services' ESD to Business, Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government has embarked on developing
electronic service delivery (ESD) of public services to business
and the community with 24-hour-a-day, seven-days-a-week access, a
government official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jessie Ting, deputy secretary for information and technology
and broadcasting, made this announcement at a press conference
here Monday on the Hong Kong Information Infrastructure Expo and
Conference slated for March 4-7 next year.
</P>
<P>
The event at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center is
organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC) and the
Information Technology and Broadcasting Bureau (ITBB).
</P>
<P>
Ting said that ITBB has formulated the "Digital 21" IT
Strategy, the primary objective of which is to promote Hong Kong's
information infrastructure and services as so to make Hong Kong a
leading digital city in a globally connected world of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
"Promotion of a wider use of IT in the community and providing
support to the IT industry are key elements of our strategy. The
coorganization of the Information Infrastructure Expo and
Conference with the TDC will contribute to our efforts in these
two areas," she explained.
</P>
<P>
An ITBB pavilion at the Expo will introduce on-line government
services and the launching of the Electronic Service Delivery
Scheme. And among other participating agencies are the Hongkong
Post, Inland Revenue Department, Information Services Department,
Office of the Telecommunications Authority and the Hong Kong
Tourist Association.
</P>
<P>
And Canada and Australia have been invited to the Expo and
Conference, under the auspices of the Memorandum of Understanding
on IT cooperation with the two countries.
</P>
<P>
TDC is committed to developing the exposition and conference
into an annual event to further promote Hong Kong as the region's
communication and IT hub, said TDC's Deputy Executive Director
Frederick Lam said at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
It is a timely project in line with the strategy outlined in
the Policy Address of Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, to make Hong
Kong a leader, not a follower, in the information world of
tomorrow, he said. The SAR government emphasized the importance
of using IT to help Hong Kong to retain its competitive edge and
to drive its overall economic expansion, he added.
</P>
<P>
The inaugural Hong Kong Information Infrastructure Expo and
Conference last year put forward many "futuristic" scenarios,
while this year's event will emphasize the actual application of
the latest electronic and information technologies in business and
in daily life.
</P>
<P>
the 1999 event includes a four-day exposition and a full-day
conference, with an expected participation of 50,000 visitors, the
organizers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
