<HEADLINE> Seoul Stock Prices Up 27 Percent Monday Morning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices on the Seoul market
on Monday soared by 27.51 percent, closing the day at 518.22, for
the first time in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Seoul stock market allowed the prices to
fluctuate 15 percent, up from the former 12 percent restriction,
under a set of new regulations introduced last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Observers and dealers said the share prices surged as South
Korean won-denominated bonds were upgraded by U.S. credit rating
agency Moody's and the restructuring of the nation's top five
family-owned conglomerates -- Hyundai, Daewoo, Samsung, LG and Sk
-- continued.
</P>
<P>
They said the stock market could experience a further rally as
investors still believed that share prices were undervalued,
predicting that the price index would rise to 550 points late this
month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South Korean won continued to appreciate Monday
morning to 1,206 against the U.S. dollar from 1,212 last weekend.
The greenback is at its lowest since July 28 this year when it
sank to 1,185 won. 
</P>
</TEXT>
