<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Detained U.N. Staff Freed in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Observer Mission in
Angola announced Monday that the 14 peacekeepers who were
detained 24 days ago by the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) had been set free.
</P>
<P>
According to a press communique issued Monday, the observers
-- ten Indians, one Bulgarian, a Swedish, a Senegalese and a
Brazilian -- who were freed last Saturday are now in "good
health."
</P>
<P>
The communique attributed the development to the great amount
of diplomatic efforts on the part of the U.N. special envoy to
Angola Issa Diallo, saying the U.N. Observer Mission is "glad" to
see the smooth settlement of the incident.
</P>
<P>
The mission also expressed gratitude to the U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan, the international community and the U.N.
Security Council for their support and encouragement.
</P>
<P>
On November 14, the opposition UNITA forces obstructed the
staff of the U.N. mission in withdrawing from the country's
central highland cities of Bailundo and Andulo with the excuse
that the airport needed "maintenance".
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the UNITA wanted to detain the
U.N. personnel as hostages in a bid to defend the military
attacks launched by the government army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
