<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stopping Companies from Dumping Goods On The Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
taking action against the dumping of industrial goods on the
domestic market, according to Bi Jingquan, director of the State
Development Planning Commission's Price Management Department.
</P>
<P>
Bi told a news conference here today that the SDPC and the
State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC) passed a regulation
last month to stop this unfair business practice.
</P>
<P>
There has been a surplus of many industrial products in China
since the start of the 1990s as a result of changes in the
international and domestic markets, leading to price-cutting
competition.
</P>
<P>
The dumping of goods at a price below cost by some enterprises
has disrupted the normal economic order, Bi says, and it is
illegal in China and an infringement on consumer rights.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation says that price management departments have
to correct or stop the selling of products at a price below either
the average industry cost or individual cost.
</P>
<P>
The government protects normal competition and respects the
rights of enterprises to set the price of their manufactured
goods, Bi says, but they must honor the principle of fair
competition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
