<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Industrial Output Up, Orders Down in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- German industrial production
increased by one percent while new orders fell by two percent in
October, the German Finance Ministry reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The October production figures were spearheaded by a 1.5
percent rise in the manufacture and mining sectors, the ministry
said. Industrial production in September registered a drop of 2.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result of stagnant construction and a 3.5 percent drop in
energy production, the combined industrial output in September and
October decreased by 2.5 percent in comparison with July and
August. However, the output figure was 2.3 percent higher than
the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said there was a continued gap between eastern and
western Germany.
</P>
<P>
In eastern Germany, production in the September-October period
was 1.4 percent higher than the same period last year, while
western Germany saw a growth rate of 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector grew by 7.8 percent and consumer goods
output surged by 19.9 percent in eastern Germany in September and
October, in comparison with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, new orders for German industry sank by 2.5 percent
in October compared with September, including a 3.5 percent
fall-off in export orders. Domestic demand was also down by two
percent during the month.
</P>
<P>
Eastern German orders in September and October were 8.3 percent
higher than the corresponding period of 1997. Western German
orders, however, were down by 0.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
