<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Congress Party Attacks Govt for Mismanagement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- India's biggest opposition
party Congress Monday attacked the government led by the Bharatiya
Janata Party (BJP) for what it called total mismanagement of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Congress members said in Rajya Sabha, the Upper House of
India's Parliament, that signs of virtual economic collapse were
evident with revenue collection falling short by 100 billion
rupees (2.35 billion U.S. dollars) during the first five months of
the current fiscal year beginning from April 1.
</P>
<P>
During a discussion of the worsening price situation and the
economic recession in the country, Pranab Mukherjee, a Congress
member, said India is heading towards a balance of payment crisis
as in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He said that the inflation rate climbed to 8.2 percent in
September from just 4.3 percent in the corresponding period of
1997.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit had doubled from 2.5 billion dollars during
the first six months of 1996-97 to about 5 billion dollars in the
April-September period this year, he said, adding that all the
economic parameters pointed to a slowdown of the economy.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released last Friday by the World Trade
Organization (WTO), India's cumulative trade figure for the first
seven months of fiscal 1998-99 went down by 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
WTO said world trade growth was estimated to fall to 4-5
percent from the projected 10 percent this year due to the
prolonged Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mukherjee, former commerce minister, criticized the government
for taking a long time to finalize the ninth five-year plan
projections, saying the first two years after the completion of
the eighth five-year plan, starting from April 1997, were actually
plan holidays.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the government had failed to take appropriate
measures for stepping up infrastructure development and it was not
feasible to raise resources for the purpose from the market as
annual interest rates were as high as 13 to 14 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
