<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Attract More Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice-President Christon
Tembo Monday urged members of the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) to create an environment that would
attract more foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Sixth Meeting of the
COMESA Council of Ministers held in Lusaka, Tembo said that, to
some extent, the success of the member states' economies in the
area of economic liberalization depends on their ability to
attract foreign direct investment and to facilitate cross border
investment.
</P>
<P>
He explained that it was due to this recognition that the
COMESA Authority, at its third summit in Kinshasa last June,
declared that the COMESA region should become a common investment
zone.
</P>
<P>
However, Tembo regretfully cited a recent U.N. report which
indicated that Africa received only 1.17 percent or 4.7 billion
U.S. Dollars out of the 95.4 billion Dollars of the world foreign
direct investment which went to developing countries in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, COMESA programs such as those on the elimination of
tariffs and non-tariff barriers, the protocol on the free
movement of persons and monetary facilitation programs are
intended to address this problem and make the region an
attractive investment area, said the vice-president.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Tembo also called on all the COMESA members to
address the challenges such as debt crisis and regional conflicts
the sub-region faces during its course of economic integration.
</P>
<P>
"Member states must endeavor to maintain peace and stability
so as to sustain the benefits of economic development. Without
peace, security and stability there can never be development or
democracy and good governance," Tembo stressed.
</P>
<P>
As for the debt crisis, he said more than 50 percent of the
members' export earnings go into debt repayment, so they should
collectively address to find "appropriate" solutions.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting with the theme of "Information: A Tool
for Increased Trade and Investment" attracted ministers and other
senior officials from 21 member states.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, which was established in 1994 to replace former
Preferential Trade Area for Eastern and Southern Africa (PTA),
aims to achieve a free trade area by the year 2000 and a customs
union with a common external tariff by the year 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
