<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Returns to Hospital After Three Hours at Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
returned to hospital mid-day on Monday, after three hours work in
the Kremlin where he sacked four key advisors.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in the Kremlin early Monday after a 15-day stay in
the Central Clinical Hospital for pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his arrival at the Kremlin, Yeltsin fired
Valentin Yumashev, head of the presidential administration, and
named Nikolai Bordyuzha, secretary of the Russian Security
Council, to replace him.
</P>
<P>
No reason was given for removing Yumashev, but it is understood
that his resignation had been sought for some time.
</P>
<P>
First deputy head of administration Yuri Yarov and deputy heads
of administration Mikhail Komissar and Yevgeny Savostyanov were
also dismissed.
</P>
<P>
Yumashev, Yeltsin's chief of staff for more than two years, had
influence well beyond his job title. He was believed to be
instrumental in many government reshuffles in the past.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old Yumashev began working for Yeltsin in the late
1980s. He has avoided cameras and interviews, and those who know
him say he is amiable, tough and determined. His relationship
with Yeltsin is said to be almost as close as son to father.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was hospitalized on November 22 with a temperature of
38.9 degrees and diagnosed to be suffering pneumonia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
