<HEADLINE> 4 Countries Split Golds in Asian Games Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea, DPR Korea,
Kazakhstan and host Thailand each claimed a gold medal on the
opening day of the shooting competitions at the Asian Games here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's Vladimir Guchsha won his first title in major
competition in the men's free pistol, scoring a total of 657.8
points, while South Korea's Kim Jung-Mi carried home the women's
air rifle gold.
</P>
<P>
Hosts Thailand struck gold when their sharpshooters smashed the
Asian Games record on their way to the women's air rifle team
title, whereas the men's free pistol team gold went to the DPR
Korea.
</P>
<P>
Asian shooting powerhouse China failed to beat jinx on Monday
and just got two silvers and as many bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Guchsha, 31, was all smiles after the free pistol final,
saying it needed mental strength to become a champion.
</P>
<P>
"After the qualification round I was very confident that I
would win the gold medal," said Guchsha. "During the final I lost
my confidence for a while but I quickly regained it."
</P>
<P>
Atlanta Olympic Games silver medalist Wang Yifu grabbed the
silver medal with 655.5 points while DPR Korea's Kim Jong-Su
finished third just 0.1 points behind.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who at 38 helped China win the world championship in
July, said: "I did not produce a good enough performance today. I
have been troubled with allergic problems these days so I was not
on peak form."
</P>
<P>
Another DPR Korea finalist Kim Hyon-Ung, who led Guchsha by 0.7
points before the 10th and last shot, notched a poor 5.5 points to
concede the title to Guchsha. He eventually finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
In the team event, world champions China finished behind DPR
Korea for the silver, followed by Japan at third place.
</P>
<P>
In the women's air rifle, South Korea's Kim Jung-Mi produced
stable performance, scoring 102.6 points in the final for a total
of 498.6 points.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Thanyarat Pupiromchaikul took the silver at 496.6
while China's Zhao Yinghui was third at 495.0.
</P>
<P>
Zhao, 17, said: "I was better in the final than qualification.
I felt no pressure at all and it might be the techinical details
that mattered."
</P>
<P>
In the team event, Thailand scored 1,178 to better the Games
record of 1,172 points set by China at Beijing in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Thai team are comprised of Pupiromchaikul, Kerdsumran
Nuanwan and Dangpiam Jarintorn.
</P>
<P>
South Korea finished second at 1,171 points while world
championships runner-up China won the bronze by scoring 1,169.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the lucklaster results from the Chinese shooters,
Chinese head coach Zhang Heng said: "We had expected two or three
golds but they performed really erraticlly... We hope to make up
for that in the other competitions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
