<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Indonesia's Reform Path Beset With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- After 32 years under the New
Order Government led by former president Soeharto, Indonesia
entered a new era of reform in mid-1998. But it seems the reform
path is beset with brambles, and most analysts say that the
success of political reform will largely depend on next year's
crucial general election.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who was elected acting president by the Provisional
People's Consultative Assembly in March 1967 and president in
March 1968, was forced to step down on May 21 and hand over the
presidency to then vice president B.J. Habibie amid the country's
worst political and economic crisis in decades.
</P>
<P>
However, the radical changes in the country were followed by
widespread social unrest. Rioting, burning and looting that broke
out in the capital city of Jakarta and some other cities in May
claimed nearly 1,300 lives and damaged over 5,000 shops and homes.
</P>
<P>
The May 13-15 riots were triggered by the killing of six
students by security persons on May 12. The students were staging
demonstrations, demanding total political, economic and legal
reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
Observers held that the turbulence not only prompted Soeharto's
downfall but also brought the crisis-hit economy to the brink of
collapse. Following the riots, most foreign investors pulled out
their capital.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the grim situation, Habibie's "Reform
Development Cabinet" pledged to speed up reforms in all fields and
keep the government free from corruption, collusion and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, under a consensus between the government and the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), a special MPR session was
convened on November 10-13, during which the five MPR factions
agreed to advance the time schedule of the next general election
from 2002 to June 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, in order to gain the trust of the people, the Habibie
government promised to hold a free and fair election. The
government said it will invite observers from the United Nations
Development Program, the United States, Germany, France, Japan and
Australia to see for themselves if Indonesia's general election is
held democratically.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the general session of the MPR will be held on August
28, 1999 instead of at the end of 1999. At the session the elected
MPR members will elect a new president and a vice president who
will lead Indonesia into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
As Indonesia's political tempo sped up, students continued to
take to the streets, demanding a thorough investigation into
Soeharto's allegedly ill-gotten wealth as well as abuses of power
conducted during his 32 years in power, and an end to the
military's socio-political role.
</P>
<P>
Massive student protests during the special MPR session in
November escalated into bloody clashes between the students and
security forces, in which 14 including nine students were killed.
The clashes were Jakarta's worst violence since the riots in May.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to mounting public pressure, Habibie issued a decree
on December 3 ordering Attorney General Ghalib to speed up the
investigation into Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the property of Soeharto and his family has
reached about 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some political observers have cast doubts about the seriousness
of the government's investigation in spite of Habibie's decree.
</P>
<P>
Arbi Sanit of the University of Indonesia said if the
investigation reached the courts, there would be a devastating
backlash against the whole government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the recent bloody clashes between Muslims and
Christians have highlighted centuries-old communal splits that
some analysts warn are the greatest threat to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of Indonesia's 202 million people are Muslims,
with the rest belonging to Christian, Buddhist and other faiths.
</P>
<P>
At least 13 people died on November 22 in Central Jakarta
during clashes between Muslims and Christians, sparking a spate of
retaliation attacks. Fifteen mosques were burned or ransacked on
November 30 in the East Nusa Tenggara capital of Kupang. Angry
Muslim mobs on December 4 burned down a church in the South
Sulawesi capital of Ujungpandang, prompting local Christians to
flee to other regions.
</P>
<P>
Some people believe that the latest clashes, like the earlier
political bloodshed, were engineered as part of a battle between
elites seeking to advance their own agendas.
</P>
<P>
"Several groups are using the current social and economic
crisis to fuel the situation for their own political ambitions,"
said Abdurrahman Wahid, who heads the country's largest Muslim
Group Nahdlatul Ulama.
</P>
<P>
Political observers believe that the government's current
challenge is to create a system that is both democratic and stable
and allows for smooth transition of power and a strong
representative government.
</P>
<P>
As national newspapers put it, after 53 years of independence,
Indonesians deserve justice and better welfare. They have seen
enough wrongdoing of the New Order rule, and they can't afford to
see another May or November bloody incident.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian politicians have urged everybody to focus efforts on
making the reform era a reality. And next year's general election
is a crucial moment for the political future of the world's fourth
most populous country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's World Heritage Sites (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Summer Palace and the
Temple of Heaven have been added to the World Heritage list of
sites during the 22nd meeting of the UNESCO's World Heritage
Committee in Japan, bringing the number of Chinese sites to a
total of 21.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has the largest number of sites.
</P>
<P>
The 21 sites that were added to the list are:
</P>
<P>
Taishan Mountain in east China's Shandong Province, a culture
and nature site, 1987;
</P>
<P>
The Great Wall near Beijing, culture site, 1987;
</P>
<P>
The Palace Museum of the Ming and Qing dynasties (1368-1911) in
downtown Beijing, culture site, 1987;
</P>
<P>
The Mogao Grottoes of Dunhuang in northwest China's Gansu
Province, culture site, 1987;
</P>
<P>
The mausoleum of Qin Shi Huang, the first emperor of Qin
Dynasty (A.D.221-206 B.C.), near Xi'an in Shaanxi Province,
culture site, 1987;
</P>
<P>
The Peking Man Site near Zhoukoudian in the southwestern
suburbs of Beijing, culture site, 1987;
</P>
<P>
Huangshan Mountain in east China's Anhui Province, culture
and nature site, 1990;
</P>
<P>
Jiuzhaigou Scenic Resort in southwest China's Sichuan Province,
nature site, 1992;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese World Heritage Sites (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Huanglong Scenic Resort in Sichuan, nature site, 1992;
</P>
<P>
Wulingyuan Scenic Resort of Zhangjiajie in central-south
China's Hunan Province, nature site, 1992;
</P>
<P>
The Chengde Imperial Summer Resort and adjacent temples in
north China's Hebei Province, culture site, 1994;
</P>
<P>
Potala Palace in Lhasa, Tibet, culture site, 1994;
</P>
<P>
The Confucian Manor, Confucian Temple, and Confucian Woods in
Qufu in east China's Shandong Province, culture site, 1994;
</P>
<P>
Ancient buildings of Wudang Mountain in central China's Hubei
Province, culture site, 1994;
</P>
<P>
Lushan Mountain near city of Jiujiang in east China's Jiangxi
Province, culture site, 1996;
</P>
<P>
Emei Mountain and the Leshan Mountain Giant Buddha in
southwestern Sichuan Province, culture and nature site, 1996;
</P>
<P>
The ancient town of Pingyao in north China's Shanxi Province,
culture site, 1997;
</P>
<P>
The gardens of Suzhou city in east China's Jiangsu Province,
culture site, 1997;
</P>
<P>
The town of Lijiang in southwest China's Yunnan Province,
culture site, 1997;
</P>
<P>
The Summer Palace and the Temple of Heaven of Beijing, both
culture sites, 1998. 
</P>
