<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Gain on Strong Offshore Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
ended Monday firmer on the back of strong gains in overseas
markets and as investors positioned themselves in
telecommunication and banking stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended the day 25.4 points firmer at
2,756.1 points with the all industrials index 55.6 points up at
4,918.6. However, the resources sector was overlooked and slipped
1.4 points to 994.2 points.
</P>
<P>
Offshore, Hong Kong share prices were sharply higher after a
surprise interest rate cut by the Hong Kong Association of Banks
and the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng was 381.9 points stronger at 10,345.0 points,
while the Nikkei closed 83 points firmer at 14,723 points.
</P>
<P>
A strong finish on Wall Street last Friday also buoyed trading
with the Dow gaining 136.46 points to 9,016.14.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds &AMP; Co. broker Peter Struk said that there was a lot of
institutional buying in Telstra, Optus and the banks.
</P>
<P>
Cable and Wireless Optus topped volume - 18.53 million shares
traded while rival Telstra has also improved 28.8 cents on a
turnover of 8.46 million.
</P>
<P>
The banks also continued to perform well.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank was leading the gains in the sector up
41.2 cents, National Australia jumped 29 cents, Westpac added 17
cents while the ANZ was 9.5 cents firmer.
</P>
<P>
In other industrial stocks, global media group News Corp. was
another strong performer after a rise in the U.S. last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Qantas Airways shares continued their strong run gaining nine
cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index slipped down 3.7 points to 1,111.9 points with
the bullion price down 0.45 to 292.45 U.S. dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 268.86 million stocks traded for 736.90
million Australian dollars (449.5 million U.S. dollars), with
rising stocks outnumbering falling stocks 574 to 524 and 426
stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
