<HEADLINE> Three Parties Dominate Nigerian Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Preliminary results of
Saturday's local government elections in Nigeria show the
dominance of three parties in the polls that were contended by a
total of nine parties.
</P>
<P>
Results from 30 states show that the People's Democratic Party
(PDP) secured a landslide victory and appears certain to become
the largest party in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Independent Electoral Commission
(INEC) show that the PDP won the chairmanship in 330 local
government areas and led in 20 states as well as the Federal
Capital Territory (FCT) Abuja, mostly in the northern parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The All People's Party seized the chairmanship in 132 local
government areas and led in three states.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance for Democracy proved its dominance in the
southwest, winning the chairmanship of 96 local government areas
in Lagos, Oyo, Ogun, Ondo, Osun and other states.
</P>
<P>
The United Peoples Party, the Movement for Democracy and
Justice and the People's Redemption Party won one chairmanship
each.
</P>
<P>
A total of 774 chairmanship were at stake in Saturday's
elections, the first of a series elections under the transition
to civil rule program of the military government.
</P>
<P>
The INEC has said that only those parties securing at least
five percent of the total votes cast in at least 24 states as
well as the FCT will be qualified for elections hereafter.
</P>
</TEXT>
