<HEADLINE> S. African Police Not Hunting for Banana: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- South African police said
Monday that they were not trying to arrest Canaan Banana, the
fugitive former Zimbabwean president.
</P>
<P>
Banana, 62, was convicted of using his official position to
force members of his staff into performing homosexual acts with
him. Banana was Zimbabwean president between 1980 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe wants Banana to appear in court on Thursday when he
was to be sentenced.
</P>
<P>
However, the former president reportedly fled to Botswana and
then to South Africa shortly before the Zimbabwean High Court
found him guilty last month on 11 counts of sodomy and indecent
assault.
</P>
<P>
Homosexual is illegal in Zimbabwe, but not in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Reg Crewe, spokesman for the South African Police Service
(SAPS), told reporters that the Zimbabwean police had only asked
the South African side to locate Banana and to check whether he
had left this country.
</P>
<P>
"No warrants have been issued to apprehend Banana," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dave Bruce, executive director of Interpol in South Africa,
has also confirmed that the SAPS was not asked to apprehend
Banana, but to locate him only.
</P>
<P>
Bruce claimed that Banana has eluded after South African
President Nelson Mandela had a private meeting with him last
week. He said the police did not know Banana's identity number,
passport number or even his date of birth.
</P>
<P>
Banana's two official passports were reportedly surrendered
before he left Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
