<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christmas Season Starts Early for Australian Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar sprung a
slow leak Monday, drifting backwards in sluggish trade as the
Christmas season took hold.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange dealers said the quiet tone of the day
indicated the Christmas slowdown had started.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed here at 61.73 U.S. cents, after dropping
to a low of 61.55. It closed last Friday at 62.53 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"It was very quiet today," Westpac chief foreign exchange
dealer Peter McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
"To use an oldie but a goodie - the Aussie was so quiet today
you could almost walk up and pat it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The low in the Australian dollar against the U.S. dollar was
reached in early local trade and on the afternoon the domestic
currency remained around 61.70 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"It has been a really narrow range, it feels like the first
week of Christmas here," McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
The detractors for the Australian dollar have been the fall in
commodity prices and the concentration on failing emerging
markets.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Brazil also dented confidence in the
Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian real was weaker against the U.S. dollar as
speculation continued that Brazil's rescue package was on the
line.
</P>
<P>
"The market is very sensitive to any negative news from
emerging markets, Brazil in particular," McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
He said the main problem for the Australian dollar at the
moment was its failure to bounce.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the cross rates the Australian dollar was buying
73.41 Japanese yen from 73.93 and 1.0355 German marks from 1.0422.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
