<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada: Let Courts Determine Mrs. Marcos' Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Monday that his government will let the courts
determine the veracity of the claim of former first lady Imelda
Marcos over 500 billion pesos (12.5 billion U.S. dollars) worth of
assets allegedly held in trust by her husband's cronies.
</P>
<P>
"She has to produce all the evidence to prove all her claims,"
President Estrada said in an ambush interview.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a newspaper report quoted Mrs. Marcos as saying her
family owns practically everything in the Philippines, "from
electricity, telecommunications, airline, banking, beer and
tobacco, newspaper publishing, television stations, shipping, oil
and mining, hotels and beach resorts, down to coconut milling,
small farms, real estate and insurance."
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Marcos claimed her husband was able to gain ownership of
100 corporations after the Laurel-Langley Treaty and the Parity
Rights granted to the Americans expired, as the constitution
limited the ownership of companies in the Philippines by
foreigners to just 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
She said among the companies immediately acquired by the late
president Ferdinand Marcos were Anchor Estate Corp., Manila
Electric Co., San Miguel Corp. and Philippine Long Distance
Telephone Co.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to this, President Estrada said, "Well, the claims of
Mrs. Marcos are all claims," adding that the evidence the former
first lady said she had has yet to verified.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, even if Mrs. Marcos can prove she owns the
companies that are now in the names of her family's cronies, she
cannot just have control over them.
</P>
<P>
The former first lady has still to prove that these were not
ill-gotten, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Presidential Commission on Good Government (PCGG)
will have to examine Mrs. Marcos' evidence and find out whether
the properties were acquired through hard-earned money, or if
they were ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
"It's up to the courts, the PCGG to determine whether that is
legitimate wealth or not," the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
