<HEADLINE> Philippine Government May Have to Rescue PAL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government financial
institutions may have to rescue the financially-troubled
Philippine Airlines (PAL) even though they are not willing to do
so, an official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu told reporters that
government financial institutions may have to provide some bridge
financing for PAL to pay off its lease and rental payments for
some aircraft and to the U.S. Export-Import Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, these institutions may only agree to provide
the bridge financing if PAL continues negotiations with Cathay
Pacific Airways or some other strategic partners.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that negotiations between PAL and Cathay are
continuing with the possible entry of Singapore Airlines as an
option.
</P>
<P>
PAL is submitting a rehabilitation plan that would include a
new partner, whose name has not been revealed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Joseph Estrada told reporters here Monday
that he expects to meet again officials of Cathay Pacific this
week to discuss its possible buy into PAL.
</P>
<P>
But he said that he is not considering a government takeover of
PAL.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he remains hopeful that a solution will surface
soon to keep PAL flying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
