<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Surge Sharply Following Rate Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Share prices in Hong Kong's
stock market shot up sharply on the first trading day this week
following the announcements of rate cuts in China's mainland and
Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index (HSI) surged 465.68 points, or 4.67
percent, to close at 10,428.82 Monday.
</P>
<P>
Market turnover was 6.217 billion HK dollars (797 million U.S.
dollars), 1.706 billion HK dollars (219 million U.S. dollars) more
than that of Friday.
</P>
<P>
The HSI rose 324.94 points, or 3.26 percent, to open at
10,288.08 Monday morning. It then climbed 415.82 points, or 4.17
percent, to close the morning session at 10,378.96.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, China's Central Bank, announced
Sunday to lower the interest rates on savings deposits and loans by
an average of 0.5 percentage point from Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Association of Banks Friday lowered deposit rates
by 0.25 percent to 4.5 percent. This was the second interest rate
cut within two weeks in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
