<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Dragonair Not to Send Greeting Cards to Preserve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's regional airline
of Dragonair has decided for the second consecutive year not to
send greeting cards to its friends and business partners during
the forthcoming holiday season in a bid to help preserve the
environment.
</P>
<P>
"We will instead extend warm personal greetings to our
customers and friends," said Stanley Hui, chief executive officer
of the airline.
</P>
<P>
"By not printing some 40,000 cards and envelopes, we are able
to save as many as 10 matured trees and in turn help conserve the
environment," Hui added.
</P>
<P>
Dragonair currently operates an all-Airbus Industrie fleet of
six A330-300s and seven A320 on a network which covers 27
destinations across the Asia-Pacific region including 18 in
China's mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
