<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Says Will Not Change Plan to Visit Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen said Monday that he would not change his plan to visit Vietnam
no matter whether the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) would accept Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen made the remarks while meeting with Vietnam's new
Ambassador to Cambodia Nguyen Duy Hung. Hun Sen is set to fly to
Hanoi on December 13 to pay a two-day official visit to Vietnam at
the invitation of his counterpart Phan Van Khai. This will be Hun
Sen's first official visit abroad since he became Cambodia's new
premier on November 30.
</P>
<P>
"I will visit Hanoi on December 13 and 14. Then on December 15
and 16, I will participate in the ASEAN summit meeting or just
meet with the leaders of ASEAN countries and its dialogue
partners," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
On Cambodia's entry into ASEAN, he said, "In order to join the
ASEAN, Cambodia has made a lot of efforts, including (that) King
Norodom Sihanouk sent separate letters to each leader of the nine
ASEAN countries on December 2 to urge them to accept Cambodia as a
full member of the regional grouping at its December 15-16 meeting
in Hanoi."
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Duy Hung said that Vietnam will do its best to support
Cambodia to become an official member of ASEAN before or during
the ASEAN summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also hinted that even if Cambodia is not admitted, he
is also possible to participate in the summit as an observer.
"There is still time to make ASEAN accept Cambodia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Hor Nam Hong, Cambodia's new foreign minister, told
reporters that if Cambodia is not admitted before the summit, the
premier will return home, and Cambodia will instead send a senior
government official to the summit as observer.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, whose entry into ASEAN was postponed after the July
1997 factional fighting, is eager to join the regional group. It
is the only Southeast Asian nation that is not a member of the
grouping.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Vietnam, Hun Sen said, he will meet with
the Vietnamese prime minister, the head of the state and other
government leaders to discuss bilateral ties, border issues, oil
rights in territorial waters and cooperation in tourism and so on.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cambodia's new coalition government has won approval
from the United Nations Credentials Committee to retake the
country's seat at the U.N. General Assembly, and is expected to
return to full membership soon.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the U.N. recognition will help Cambodia's
drive to join ASEAN and attract foreign aid suspended after last
year's political crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
