<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Fires Top Aids After Returning to Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
on Monday fired Chief of Staff Valentin Yumashev, his spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted an administration official as saying that
Nikolai Bordyuzha, secretary of the Russian Security Council, will
replace Yumashev.
</P>
<P>
No reason was given by the Kremlin for Yumashev's removal, but
the former correspondent was said to have asked for resignation
for some time.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin returned to the Kremlin earlier Monday after a 15-day
stay in the Central Clinical Hospital where he was treated for
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
Yumashev's deputies Yuri Yarov, Mikhail Komissar and Yevgeny
Savostyanov were also dismissed.
</P>
<P>
Yumashev, who had influence well beyond his job title, was
believed to be instrumental in many government reshuffles in the
past, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Yumashev, a rumpled, 40-year-old ex-journalist, began working
for Yeltsin in the late 1980s. He avoids cameras and interviews,
and those who know him said he is amiable, tough and
determined. His relationship with Yeltsin is said to be almost as
close as son to father.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Yumashev's departure, former Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin said the move reflects "stagnation and lack of
initiative on the part of the presidential team."
</P>
<P>
He said that Yeltsin's decision is obviously "correct" and "is
expected to give a new impetus to the work of the presidential
administration," Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, who said Yumashev will "remain on Yeltsin's
team," noted that by taking this decision "Yeltsin has
demonstrated that he intends to serve out his term until the year
2000." 
</P>
</TEXT>
