<HEADLINE> Philippines Health Procurement Goes Internet for Scrutiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Health of the
Philippines will soon publish its procurement information on the
Internet for public scrutiny, Alberto G. Romualdez Jr., Secretary
of Health, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez told a regular press briefing that installing such
information in the department's web page is one of the features of
the department's revised procurement system, designed to prevent
alleged graft and corruption practices.
</P>
<P>
"The press," Romualdez added, "should have access to all
transactions (of the department) and if you notice anything
(questionable) that you don't like, you can report it to us or
have them published in your newspapers."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the regional health offices are required to submit
copies of the bidding results to the central office to identify
gross mistakes, Romualdez said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the department purchases one billion pesos
(25 million U.S. dollars) worth of drugs and medicines yearly,
with its central office procuring 500 million pesos (12.5 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
