<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Okays WTO Infotech Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate has
ratified the World Trade Organizations (WTO) Information
Technology (Infotech) Agreement which would phase out tariffs on
infotech products by year 2000, the Philippines News Agency said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was ratified by a vote of 19-3, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Its ratification enrolls the Philippines in the camp of 50 WTO
members which have similarly acceded to the accord, and which
together account for 92.5 percent of the total trade in the
information technology industry, it said.
</P>
<P>
Senator Blas Ople, who pushed the ratification, said the Senate
approval will enable the Philippine semi-conductor industry to
acquire more advanced equipment and be more globally competitive.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was initially tabled at the Asian-Pacific
Economic Cooperation meetings but the United States elevated it to
the WTO to make it binding on most of WTO signatory members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
