<HEADLINE> Egyptian Human Rights Group Chief Freed on Bail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the Egyptian
Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) Hafez Abu Saada has been set
free on bail, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Higher State Security Court ordered the release of Abu
Saada Sunday on 500 Egyptian pounds (147 U.S. dollars) bail, the
English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution, meanwhile, ordered the arrest of EOHR's
lawyer, Moustafa Zeidan, who prepared a report alleging police
brutality against Coptic Christians in southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Abu Saada was detained last Wednesday on charges of accepting
foreign funds for disseminating allegations detrimental to Egypt's
national interests.
</P>
<P>
The private Al Usbou weekly newspaper said last month that EOHR
had received 25,000 dollars offered by Britain after it compiled a
report claiming that more than 1,000 Copts in Egypt were rounded
up and persecuted by police in Suhag Governorate's Kosheh village.
</P>
<P>
EOHR denied the money had any connection with that report,
issued in September.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that based on the EOHR report, Britain's
Sunday Telegraph newspaper reported that "Egyptian Christians have
been subejected to horrific crucification rituals, raped and
tortured by the security forces during a crackdown on the ancient
Coptic community."
</P>
<P>
Egypt's parliament, social groups and celebrities have
denounced the story of the British newspaper as a fabrication
aimed at defaming Egypt.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Muslim majority and Christian minority have
been co-existing in peace for more than 14 centuries in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
