<HEADLINE> Japan Not to Change Stance on SDF's Role: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi said Monday that his government will maintain its current
interpretation of the country's constitution, which bars the
Self-Defense Forces (SDF) from participating in military
operations abroad.
</P>
<P>
"The current cabinet has no intention of changing the
interpretation of the Constitution," Obuchi said at the Budget
Committee of the House of Representatives to respond to a question
raised by an opposition party legislator.
</P>
<P>
Takeshi Maeda, a member of the main opposition Democratic Party
of Japan, asked Obuchi to clarify a policy agreement reached
between Obuchi and Liberal Party leader Ichiro Ozawa in
mid-November stating that Japan will "participate in
U.N. peacekeeping activities at the request of the U.N."
</P>
<P>
Ozawa has said that his agreement with Obuchi changes the
traditional interpretation of the constitution, paving the way for
SDF personnel to participate in U.N. military operations endorsed
by the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Party plans to become a coalition partner of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party. 
</P>
