<HEADLINE> Reunification Should not Be Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said
today the issue of China's reunification should not be postponed
indefinitely and urged Taiwan authorities to open cross-Straits
political talks at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Kehui, vice chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), said
Taiwan should value the progress achieved during the recent
meeting between Wang Daohan and Koo Chenfu, and should "join hands
in striving for the realization of the reunification."
</P>
<P>
Zhang made the comments at a recent forum sponsored by the
All-China Federation of Taiwan Compatriots and the Central
Committee of the Taiwan Democratic Self-Government League (TDSGL)
to mark the 20th anniversary of the Third Plenary Session of the
11th Communist Party of China Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said participants in the forum decided on the general
principle of solving the Taiwan issue through peaceful means. He
added that the mainland has worked out a series of related
policies over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, chairman of the TDSGL Central Committee, reviewed the
mainland's reunification endeavors and growing trade,
cultural and personnel across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
He said the vast majority of Taiwan compatriots hope to
maintain the status quo. "Most Taiwan compatriots think the 'one
country, two systems' principle provides the best solution."
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the TDSGL is perfectly willing to work with
Taiwan compatriots to achieve reunification. 
</P>
