<HEADLINE> Samaranch Says China Fights All-out Battle Against Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic Committee
president Juan Antonio Samaranch on Monday acknoledged China's
seriousness in its fight against doping in sports.
</P>
<P>
"I will say that maybe China is one of the countries fighting
with all its strength against doping -- and that is quite
important for the IOC," said Samaranch in a press conference on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I think today the fight against doping in China is an
example for us all."
</P>
<P>
Talking about the 2008 Olympic candidates, the president said
he encouraged all the cities to bid for the Games.
</P>
<P>
"My role is to encourage as many candidates as possible," he
said. "If I'm in China, I'll encourage China. If I'm in Japan,
I'll encourage Japan, and if it's Malaysia, I'll encourage them."
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Japanese city Osaka and Malaysian capital Kuala
Lumpur have expressed interest in hosting the 2008 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
In the press conference, Samaranch also said it was too late
for Poland and Slovakia to submit a joint bid to stage the 2006
Winter Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch expressed full support for the structure of
Sydney's Olympics Organizing Committee after a new Australian
political leader demanded change.
</P>
<P>
Kerry Chikarovski, who replaced Peter Collins as leader of
the New South Wales opposition party Monday, said she wanted the
roles of committee president and state government's Olympic
Minister to be seperated.
</P>
<P>
Michael Knight of Labor Party has both jobs but his fate will
be decided in a state election in March.
</P>
<P>
"It's up to them but if they ask me for advice I would like
them to hold the same format as there is now," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
"This closeness we have now through the government and the
organizing committee through Minister Knight is a very good one.
</P>
<P>
"These days, for the success of the games, the organizing
committee must be very, very close to the government. This
solution you have in Sydney I support 100 percent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
