<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian Refugees Fined for Free Travel in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 7 (Xinhua) - A total of 176 Burundian
refugees at Lukole camp in northwestern Tanzania's Kagera Region
have been fined 50,000 Shillings (about 73 US Dollars) each or
six-month imprisonment for leaving their camp.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Home Affairs Ministry confirmed a press
report here Monday, saying that 50 others have been sentenced 20
strikes of the cane by the Bukoba district court for attempting
to escape from their camp.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Kagera Regional Police Commander Eliyuko
Elihaki as saying that all the 226 refugees were netted in a
police swoop on November 30 when they were on their way to the
Nduta refugee camp in three trucks.
</P>
<P>
"They were apparently going to join other refugees from
Burundi in Kigoma region," Elihaki said.
</P>
<P>
The Commander said the fleeing refugees were returned to
Bukoba last Monday where all pleaded guilty to two separate
counts before Resident Magistrate R.M. Ruhasha.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were accused of conspiracy and violation of the
Tanzanian Refugees Act approved recently for restricting free
movement from camps in a way to keep local society in order.
</P>
<P>
"We have sent them back to Lukole camp. The court has given
them six months to pay the fine, failing which they would be
jailed for six months each," Elihaki said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Tanzanian drivers of the trucks pleaded
guilty to colluding with the refugees and were jailed for 18
months each.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that by the end of last week, a total of
20,000 refugees from the neighboring Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) and Burundi have so far entered Tanzania since a bloody
crisis broke out in DRC early August.
</P>
<P>
Among them are 15,619 refugees from the DRC and 3,846 from
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Their arrivals have brought the grand total refugees from the
two countries currently in the refugee camps in western Tanzania
to 236,425. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
