<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has 21 World Heritage Sites (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- China ranks fourth in the world
with 21 sites listed on UNESCO's list of World Heritages,
including the Summer Palace and the Temple of Heaven.
</P>
<P>
China applied for World Heritage status for its most famous
imperial park and largest sacrificial temple in June of
1998. UNESCO's World Heritage Committee has since added the
palace, a 290-ha. part of the emperors of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1011) after 1888, and the temple which covers some 2.7
million square meters to the list of World Heritages.
</P>
<P>
The two sites attract millions of visitors from both home and
abroad each year.
</P>
<P>
The logo for China's tourism department depicts the Hall of
Prayer for Good Harvests in the Temple of Heaven.
</P>
<P>
"People worldwide will treasure the Temple of Heaven even more
and will provide more effective protection since the complex was
added to the list," according to Lou Lianju, director of the
temple's Administrative Office.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of European and American visitors to the
temple increased dramatically during the application process.
</P>
<P>
Lou and his colleagues are determined to restore the ancient
appearance of the altar as part of an extensive long-term
protection project.
</P>
<P>
The World Heritage Committee, established in 1976, requires the
preservation of the original features of both cultural and natural
sites, and has established special funds for protection
projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Home to 21 World Heritage Sites (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cultural sites are required to have historic, artistic,
archeological, scientific and anthropological value, while natural
sites must offer distinct ecological and geographical features.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on the Protection of World Cultural and Natural
Heritages, which UNESCO adopted in 1972, requires all contracting
members to fully preserve and safeguard listed sites which are
defined as safe areas during times of war.
</P>
<P>
A total of 582 cultural and natural sites worldwide are
included on the list of World Heritages.
</P>
<P>
The committee acts in accordance with the convention and not
only provides both financial and administrative services to
countries will relates sites, but also conducts preservation
research.
</P>
<P>
China joined the convention in 1985 and filed application for
World Heritages the following year. Six Chinese sites were added
to to the list in 1987 -- Mount Taishan in east Shandong Province;
the Great Wall and the Palace Museum in Beijing; the Mogao
Grottos in Dunhuang, Gansu Province; the Tomb of Qinshihuang in
Xi'an; and the Peking Man site near Zhoukoudian in southwest
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Potala Palace in Lhasa, Tibet, as well the Lushan Mountains
in Jiangxi Province, the city gardens in Suzhou in Jiangsu
Province, and the ancient town of Lijiang in Yunnan Province are
also on the list.
</P>
<P>
China submits a limited number of applications each year, and
priority currently focuses on gaining a listing for Wuyi Mountains
in Fujian Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Efforts to Monitor Somali Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has called
for support and co-operation from the international community in
monitoring Somali coastline following reports of toxic dumping,
piracy and illegal fishing there.
</P>
<P>
The call followed a statement by Captain Edward Johns Jr, who
is heading a U.N. Conference on Trade and Development project to
rehabilitate the northern Somali ports of Bossaso and Bersseba,
the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The risk of oil pollution, given the volume of traffic around
the Horn of Africa, was high and possible repercussions great, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Johns noted that illegal fishing was another source of major
concern in the Horn of Africa and required close attention from
the international community as well.
</P>
<P>
Tuna stocks in the region, especially around the northern
Somali coast, were substantial, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We know that reputable and disreputable fishing concerns are
fishing in this region, paying no license fees, taking fish and
simply leaving the Somali coast," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that there is no internationally recognized state
governing this region should not stop the international community
from intervening," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that the administrations emerging along the
Somali coast had realized the gravity of the problem and felt
they should act.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Computers on Sale in U.S. Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 6 (Xinhua) -- AutoPC, a computer inside
cars put out by a California-based car radio maker, went on sale
at some stores in Seattle, San Diego and San Francisco this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Clarion Corp., the AutoPC maker, demonstrated the device in a
bright yellow, convertible Mercedes, while explaining AutoPC
functions in detail on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
The computer runs Microsoft's Windows CE, a version of Windows
for handheld PCs and consumer electronics devices, as its
operating system and slides into the car-radio slot.
</P>
<P>
According to Clarion, the computer integrates car audio,
computing functions, navigation and wireless communications
through hand-free voice activation within the dash of a car.
</P>
<P>
The unit recognizes over 200 voice commands and with its
text-to-speech application, reads e-mail and provides other
information such as turn-by-turn directions and status
information, weather reports, traffic alerts and assistance all
via "speech synthesis."
</P>
<P>
While the functions may be useful to a long-distance driver,
the price of the system is not cheap. To get the full package, a
user will have to spend between 2,200 and 2,500 U.S. dollars. The
basic AutoPC, containing voice-activated radio and mapping
capabilities, also cost about 1,300 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Observers worry the device will cause the users to take their
eyes off the road, but according to the maker, the device may
actually make driving safer by providing directions when a user is
lost. In addition, the driver will never have to take his hands
off the wheel.
</P>
<P>
ZD Net News, an Internet news medium, quoted Microsoft
officials as saying that an updated version of the car computer is
due out next year. Future versions of Microsoft and other software
developers will contain more features, such as monitoring a car's
engine, and connecting to sensors in a car's bumper that will tell
drivers the safe distance behind them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
