<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Million S. Africans Registered for General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 7 (Xinhua) -- About 40 percent of South
Africa's estimated 25 million potential voters might have
registered for next year's general election by Sunday, according
to the Independent Electoral Commission (IEC).
</P>
<P>
More data are coming in and the exact number could only be
known later this week.
</P>
<P>
The IEC found that more women (3.2 million) than men (2.5
million) had enrolled.
</P>
<P>
It also found that there was a high degree of apathy among
young voters. In the 16 to 18 age group, about half of whom
would be eligible to vote by next year, only about 2.3 percent
had registered.
</P>
<P>
The highest registration rate (33.9 percent) was among the 70
to 80 age group.
</P>
<P>
Those who have not registered would be given a second chance
early next year. The dates will be announced this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
