<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Community Urged to Invest in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has urged U.S. business community to invest
in Nigeria as the country is rich in resources and manpower.
</P>
<P>
The head of state made the remarks when he received the
visiting United States Commerce Secretary, William Daley, who
arrived in Nigerian capital Abuja on Sunday, the Daily Times
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that democracy had come to stay in the country
following the impressive conduct of Saturday's local government
elections, adding that "It (democracy) will stay."
</P>
<P>
Daley said he is visiting Nigeria at a key moment in the
country's history, adding "the world is waiting for Nigeria to
emerge as a potential trading partner".
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, the U.S. secretary said his message to
the Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar was that "if
Nigeria keeps on the path of reform, American companies will be
there to help you build a market-based democracy."
</P>
<P>
Daley told American and Nigerian business communities that
"there has to be real commitment from the Nigerian leaders to
make this economy attractive for long-term trade and investment."
</P>
<P>
According to him, many U.S. companies have strong ties with
the west African country and they want to build on the basis of
those ties if the climate is right.
</P>
<P>
Daley urged Nigeria to adopt a fully convertible currency with
a single market-determined exchange rate, so that investment can
flow unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
Noting the recent changes taking place in the most populous
African country, Daley said the U.S. would like to see real
progress on the privatization of public-owned enterprises in
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to hearing more about privatizing
government-run businesses, including electric power,
telecommunications and fertilizer production," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Nigeria must co-operate on the controlling of
drug trafficking and reduction in crime rate in order "to regain
access to the U.S. government and international financing".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
