<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Emigrants Rescued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen Chinese citizens
attempting to illegally emigrate to the Republic of Korea (ROK)
were recently rescued after drifting at sea for several days.
</P>
<P>
The illegal emigrants from the east China city of Fuzhou were
15 to 40 years old. They were abandonded at sea by smugglers and
eventually rescued by the crew of fishing boat from east
China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The illegal emigrants left their home at the end of September
and later they were robbed of all their personal belongings,
including cash and identification cards.
</P>
<P>
The fishing boat rescued the victims on October 13 after five
days adrift. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Target Tariff Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Most members of the Common
Market for the Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) will be ready
to effect a 90-percent tariff reduction by 1999 in the ongoing
run-up to the implementation of a free trade zone by 2000.
</P>
<P>
A document adopted here by the sixth meeting of the COMESA
inter-governmental committee said many member countries have
submitted details of areas where they need to remove tariff
barriers.
</P>
<P>
Up to date the members have effected various levels of tariff
reduction rates ranging from 60 to 80 percent, the ultimate
target is for all the members to achieve zero-rate tariffs by
2000.
</P>
<P>
The process is ongoing and requires continuous consultation
due to the complicated nature of the subject matter.
</P>
<P>
The inter-government committee has also recommended that the
African, Caribbean and Pacific countries (ACP) should give
assistance to COMESA members in the coordination of negotiations
for a post Lome IV trade and cooperation status with European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The current phase of the Lome convention, which is the fourth
in the series, ends in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
COMESA members are keen to negotiate for conducive
arrangements in the future relations between the EU and ACP
countries which will help their relatively weaker countries in a
market dictated competition for trade opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
