<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Police Seize Fake Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 7 (Xinhua) -- In one of the biggest round-up
operations in Lebanon's history, the police have netted a gang of
counterfeiters and seized some 5 million U.S. dollars in fake
currency, the Daily Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
After a car chase in which two police corporals sustained minor
injuries, three men were arrested in downtown Beirut Sunday and 5
million worth of freshly-printed counterfeit dollars were
confiscated, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese national Abdel Nasser Hanafi, 28, Nigeria Charles
Odiri, 26, and Lebanese Ibrahim Ali Khaled, 33, were taken into
custody for allegedly planning to use the fake money.
</P>
<P>
However, the alleged American mastermind of the gang,
Chicago-born Tony Scott, 36, managed to escape from the West
House hotel in Beirut where the film negatives used for
counterfeiting process were found, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
The film negatives had an 80 percent accuracy capacity, the
highest one ever discovered in Lebanon's counterfeit industry,
said the police sources.
</P>
<P>
The counterfeit notes had reportedly been shown to the
country's most experienced money exchangers who could not detect
any difference from legal tender notes.
</P>
<P>
U.S. experts in counter-terrorism are expected to arrive
Monday from Cyprus to examine the notes and help in the
investigations, as part of a bilateral agreement to fight
terrorism between Lebanon and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
