<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Migratory Birds Frequent Liaoning Sanctuaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- People living around the
national nature reserve in Panjin, northeastern China's Liaoning
Province, persist in their annual tradition of providing ample
dried fish and corn for migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
Local provision feeds the birds an estimated 4,000 kg of fish
and corn each year.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, a key national nature preservation zone, serves as
an important stopover for migratory water birds from east Asia and
Australia. The provincial government has opened three sanctuaries
over the past 10 years for the large number of birds arriving in
early spring and late autumn.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 500 cranes, as well as 30,000 geese and duck will
visit the sanctuaries on this year's trip south.
</P>
<P>
Panjin, an area famous for a good environment, is the natural
habitat of more than 200 first- and second-class species under the
state protection, including red-crowned cranes and black-billed
gulls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
