<HEADLINE> Thai Government Backs Plane Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai Airways International
(THAI) has won the government support for switching plans to lease
aircraft to buying new ones, airline sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The airways' proposal to buy two Boeing jumbos worth 282.21
million U.S. dollars has been approved by the cabinet, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
THAI had previously relied on leasing aircraft for its
operations. It changed the policy after reasoning that leasing
would be more costly in the long run.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Communications Minister Suthep Thueksuban said
THAI has the power to decide whether to go ahead with its purchase
plans since the cabinet has approved the new procurement plan.
</P>
<P>
THAI management suggested that a plan to lease the 149.23
million U.S. dollar Boeing 747-400 and a 132.98 million dollar
Boeing 777-300 be switched back to an original plan to buy the
planes as, in the long run, leasing would be more costly.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Communications secretary general Mahidol
Chantrangkoon, in his capacity as THAI board chairman, said he had
ordered THAI management to explain the change in writing.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet considered the purchase proposal which was
submitted to the cabinet by both the finance and transport
ministries. The Finance Ministry is THAI's largest shareholder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
