<HEADLINE> Namibian High Court Judge Killed in Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibian High Court Judge
Fonnie Karuaihe died in a car accident in the Gobabis Area in
eastern Namibia on Sunday morning, South African Press
Association reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Karuaihe was killed instantly when his vehicle overturned
after his driver swerved to avoid hitting a kudu, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Two other people in the car were also injured, but are out of
danger.
</P>
<P>
Karuaihe, 38, was appointed as a judge in January this year.
He was the youngest Namibian to hold such a position.
</P>
<P>
Apart from being the first attorney to be elevated to the
bench, Karuaihe was only the second black Namibian to be
appointed as a permanent high court judge.
</P>
<P>
Karuaihe grew up in Windhoek, the capital of Namibia, and
studied at the Western Cape Province in South Africa where he
graduated with a bachelor of commerce degree in 1980, followed by
a bachelor of law degree.
</P>
<P>
He is survived by his wife and three children. 
</P>
