<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stock Market Dips This year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' stock market
dipped to 875.4 billion pesos (21.88 billion dollars) in October
from 2,346.0 billion pesos (58.65 billion U.S. dollars) in January
1997 due to weak confidence of foreign investors, the Philippine
News Agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gilbert G. Garchitorena, a professor of economics at the
University of Asia and the Pacific, was quoted by the agency as
saying that the turbulence in the Philippine equities market is
its heavy reliance on foreign investments to fuel an upsurge in
stock prices and volume turnover.
</P>
<P>
Contributing to the fall from January 1997 to October 1998 was
the property and financial sectors of the equities market which
performed poorly, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that this was due to continued fears of a glut in the
real estate sector and the weakness of the banks' balance sheets,
thus resulting in a shrink of the banks' index and the financial
services index by 46.0 percent and 34.3 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Also contributing to the decline was the oil index which posted
a 45.5 percent drop in the same period, Garchitorena said.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, he said, the drop in the Phisix index led to the
decline of the average daily value turnover from 2.7 million pesos
(67,500 dollars) in 1996 to a dismal 1.5 million pesos (37,500
dollars) in the first nine months of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
