<HEADLINE> Congolese (K) Nationals in Zambia Call for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Congolese nationals in Zambia
have called for setting up a combined peacekeeping force by the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and United Nations in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
In a five-point plan to help restore peace in DRC, they also
called for disarming all fighting forces and pull-out of all
foreign forces in the war-torn country, Times of Zambia reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jean Ng'andu, spokesman of a non-political organization called
the Syndicate for the Voice and the Interests of the Nation
(SVIN), unveiled the peace plan here in the capital.
</P>
<P>
He said a neutral electoral commission should be constituted
to prepare for polls under free and fair conditions.
</P>
<P>
The elections should be held under neutral international
observers to ensure they are free and fair and an agreement
should be reached for all contestants to accept the results, he
said.
</P>
<P>
After the elections, the involvement of Rwanda and Uganda in
the DRC crisis should be discussed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ng'andu challenged the people involved in the war to give
peace a chance if they are really fighting for national
interests. 
