<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Enterprises Expect Double-Digit Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Township enterprises in China
are expected to achieve this year's projected 18 percent economic
growth rate in spite cutthroat competition and the ongoing
financial crisis sweeping Asia, the Ministry of Agriculture said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Yongtao, director of the ministry's Township Enterprise
Bureau, pointed out that the cumulative growth rate of township
enterprises topped 16.9 percent for the January-October
period. And the growth rate would hit 18.1 percent if the sector
maintains an average monthly increase of 0.6 percent through the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks at the 1998 Cooperative Economic and
Trade Meeting of National Township Enterprises held in Zhumadian
Prefecture, central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin praised the role township enterprises
play in national economy and urged localities to pay greater
attention to the sector's development during an April visit to
Jiangsu Province. Governments departments at all levels have since
increased policy-making and funding efforts to support township
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Related enterprises are also benefiting from government
policies designed to stimulate the economy by increasing funding
for infrastructure, expanding domestic demand and exploring rural
markets. For example, investments of some 100 billion yuan (12.5
billion US dollars) in infrastructure have helped produce some 60
percent of the total output value for township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China's massive efforts to eliminate smuggling and
encourage foreign trade have helped increase the export volume for
township enterprises. Statistics show that township enterprises
enjoyed a 10.7-percent rise in exports for the January-October
period.
</P>
<P>
Increased investments in science and technology, as well as in
technological upgrading, have also helped maintain the high growth
rate for township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises, the brainchild of Chinese farmers, have
not only played a leading role in the rural economy, but accounted
for increasing contributions to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture statistics indicate that a three to
four percentage points rise or fall in the growth rate for
township enterprises will result in a one percentage point change
in the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Perhaps more importantly, however, is the fact that
China's 24 million township enterprises employ 130 million rural
laborers, or close to half of the surplus rural labor force.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 growth rate for township enterprises is expected to be
set at 15 percent to help them improve industrial structure and
product mix for better performance in the future, according to
Jiang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
