<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Bill Threatens Kenya's Health Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's expenditure on caring
for AIDS patients is soaring dramatically and will equal about
half of the entire public health budget by the year 2000,
according to a top-level anti-AIDS project.
</P>
<P>
The total hospital costs for AIDS care will amount to some 63
million U.S. Dollars by 2000, and to 90 million Dollars by 2005,
the National AIDS and STDs Control Program (NASCOP) warned.
</P>
<P>
The total direct and indirect costs of AIDS is also shooting
up from about two to four percent of the gross domestic product
in 1991 to 15 percent at the turn of the century, the East
African weekly quoted a new NASCOP report as saying.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 1.5 million people in Kenya, about nine percent
of the total population, are currently infected with the HIV
virus which can cause the vital AIDS. It is predicted that the
number will be 1.8 million by 2000 and 2.1 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the AIDS patients will occupy more than 50
percent of all hospital beds in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first AIDS case was detected in the east African country
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
These figures are based on the country's HIV sentinel
surveillance program, which operates in 13 urban and 11 rural
sites around the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 08:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Claims Environmental Damage by Iraqi Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait has claimed over 16 billion U.S. dollars in environmental
damages to Kuwait, a local newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Al-Anba newspaper, Adel Asem,
deputy chairman of the public authority for assessment of
compensations for damages resulting from the Iraqi invasion, said
even this figure "was not final."
</P>
<P>
This was "because a large portion of the environmental claims
primarily depends on results of long and thorough studies and
researches," Asem said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Kuwait would present at the end of next February
two types of claims to the United Nations Compensations Commission
(UNCC) including mines eradication from the deserts and researches
and studies claims.
</P>
<P>
The UNCC attaches great importance to environmental claims,
Asem said, and added that Iraqi invasion also caused environmental
damages to the neighboring countries of both Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia was severely hit by the oil leakage into its
coast, he said, anticipating its environmental claims to be very
high.
</P>
<P>
Asem said that Iran's coast was also inflicted great damages
due to the impact of smokes of Kuwait's burning oil wells which
had covered a large part of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Other countries in the region including Jordan and Syria have
also presented their claims to the UNCC as they suffered acid
rains which brought tremendous impact on their environment, Asem
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
