<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Astronauts aboard the space shuttle Endeavor
Sunday successfully connected the first two elements for the
international space station.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the two elements -- Zarya built by
Russia and put into space on November 20 and Unity built by NASA
-- to be docked 240 miles above the Earth, and thus paved the way
for the next 5 years' assembly of the international space
station. The two station pieces are very big -- 77 feet from the
tip of one to the tip of the other with a total mass of 70,000
pounds, like a seven-story tower in the shuttle cargo bay.
(US-Space Station)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan said here Sunday
that he will accept any decision over his case made by Italy or
European Union, if the international community pledges to take
concrete steps to resolve the Kurdish issue.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan told Italian news agency ANSA that an Italian-backed
proposal for him to be tried in an international court would be
the best possible solution. Ocalan was arrested by Italy after
flying into Rome from Moscow on November 12. As the leader of
Kurdistan Worker Party, he is Turkey's most wanted man. Italy's
rejection over Turkish demands for his extradition has caused a
crisis in relations between the two countries. (Italy-Ocalan-Trial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- United Kingdom Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said on
Sunday that he is "very encouraged" by U.N. chief Kofi Annan's
talks with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi about the Lockerbie
suspects.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in an interview with the BBC television
after speaking to the United Nations Secretary-General, who held
talks with Gaddafi late on Saturday. Cook said it was "possible"
that the two Libyans, who were accused of bombing in December 21,
1988, could be in custody by the 10th anniversary of the bombing.
(UK-Annan-Lockerbie Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Clashes between Palestinian protesters and Israeli
troops in the West Bank continued Sunday, wounding at least two
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The clashes took place outside the Jewish settlement of Ariel
in northern West Bank when Palestinian demonstrators threw stones
at Israeli soldiers, who fired rubber bullets and tear gas in
response. The clashes stemmed from an increasingly bitter row over
Palestinian prisoners to be released under the Wye agreement
signed on October 23. (Palestine-Israel-Prisoners) 
</P>
