<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yi Ethnic Group in the Midst of Change (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Editor's Note: This is the
eighth of a series of stories featuring the fast-changing life and
culture of the Zhuang, Yi, Miao, Yao and other seven main ethnic
groups in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, which
will mark its 40th founding anniversary on December 11.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Yi ethnic group were living a primitive tribal
society when Red Army Commander Liu Bocheng and a Yi chieftain
reached an agreement enabling the former's forces to pass through
the area on the historic Long March (1934-35).
</P>
<P>
Life of the Yi, an ethnic group which lives mainly in the
Daliang and Xiaoliang mountains in Sichuan Province, as well as in
Guangxi and Yunnan Province, has changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
De'e Township in northwestern Guangxi is home to over 1,600 Yi
people. Chieftains no longer rule and Huang Wenli, a member of the
Yi group and deputy Party secretary in De'e, is the
highest-ranking official in the township.
</P>
<P>
The Yi represent a minority in the township inhabited by members
of other ethnic groups including the Miao, Gelao, Han and Zhuang,
and the number of the Miao people alone is more than 10,000.
</P>
<P>
Former customs prohibited intermarriages between members of the
Yi and Miao. Today, however, the older generation accepts
intermarriages based on mutual affection.
</P>
<P>
Huang married his wife, a member of the Gelao ethnic group, in
1986.
</P>
<P>
"We were the first couple in the township to receive a marriage
certificate," said Huang, adding that "few people in local ethnic
areas registered for marriage at that time, and most simply opted
to live together.
</P>
<P>
"Registering is more appropriate, and offers certain advantages
in case of future disputes."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yi People (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The township now requires villagers to register for marriage in
accordance with the Marriage Law, said Huang.
</P>
<P>
A number of old Yi marriage customs have in fact been
abandoned. For example, male cousins, regardless of how poor, had
priority when it came to marrying female cousins. However, the
custom of marriage between cousins was abandoned a number of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The Yi continue to celebrate the traditional Torch Festival set
on June 24 every year according to the Lunar Calendar. Members of
the ethnic group burn torches for three days and nights to drive
away insects the legendary "King of Heaven" sent to eat crops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yi villagers also sacrifice pigs and cows during
memorial ceremonies for their ancestors. In the evening, they walk
around their fields with torches, and gather around bonfires to
sing, dance and play musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
Li Jingxing, a Yi farmer in De'e Township, said members of the
ethnic group living in Guangxi can only speak the Yi language. He
added that the written language has virtually disappeared.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed hope that members of the group living Sichuan and
Yunnan will help Guangxi's Yi recover the written language.
</P>
<P>
"While it's convenient to use Putonghua (the standard Chinese
language), we still want to retain our ethnic language," said Li.
</P>
<P>
The unique folklore in De'e Township has attracted the
attention of artists from the United States, Thailand, Hong Kong
and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Huang's greatest ambition is to construct an asphalt road
linking the township with the outside world. He pointed out that
"a road will enable us to develop tourism."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
