<HEADLINE> Death Fear Grows as Arsonist Hits Wellington Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Suspicious fires in
Wellington,
the capital of New Zealand, have been increased to 21 since
mid-September
and fear heightened that a serial arsonist may be just a step away
from
killing someone.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported Monday that there were another two
suspicious
fires in central Wellington Sunday, one at a house and another at
a hall.
</P>
<P>
Wellington district police manager Gerry Cunneen said that
despite
extensive investigations police are "sadly no closer to catching
the
arsonist than they were two weeks ago."
</P>
<P>
"We have no idea whether this is a male, female, child or
adult.
There's been no physical profile presented to us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Police said that it was lucky that the sole occupant of the
house was
awake watching videos about three o'clock a.m. when she smelt
smoke
coming from the lower area of her two-storeyed home.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-September, Wellington has seen a spate of suspicious
fires,
mostly at wooden homes and often in the early hours.
</P>
<P>
On November 7, an arsonist with low intelligence was caught in
Upper
Hutt, a district under Wellington administration. But he was later

confirmed to have nothing to do with the spate of fires in
central
Wellington.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, Wellington police urged local residents to come
forward
with information as a potentially life-threatening arsonist
continued to
elude them. A team composed of detectives has been concentrating
on the
case and all police resources are available to it.
</P>
<P>
Cunneen said police fears are growing that "someone would be
seriously injured or killed" as the spate of arsons continues.
</P>
<P>
It is impossible to tell if the arsonist is deliberately
setting out
to kill someone, he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged local people to remain "calm but vigilant" and report
"any
signs of suspicious activity". 
</P>
</TEXT>
