<HEADLINE> Athletics Canada Say No to Disgraced Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's athletics federation
has refused to reinstate disgraced sprinter Ben Johnson,
disqualified for doping after winning the 100 meters at the 1988
Seoul Olympics, according to Sunday's Toronto Sun.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Athletics Canada, which examined the athlete's
request at its general assembly on Saturday at Ottawa, did not
see a reason to welcome him back into the field until all
possible appeal avenues had been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to do anything above and beyond what we think
is the best system in the world, one that's fair and equitable to
all athletes," said Athletics Canada president Rolf Lund.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, 36, has not competed professionally since the IAAF
handed him a life suspension in 1993 after he returned two
positive tests - first when being stripped of his 1988 gold medal
and then five years later after a meeting in Montreal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
