<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Household Savings Slump in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Household savings in New
Zealand
slumped by 800 million NZ dollars (424 million U.S. dollars) in
the third
quarter this year, The Dominion reported Monday while quoting the
latest
EquitiLink savings indicator.
</P>
<P>
EquitiLink is an independent managed investment company with
6.5
billion NZ dollars (3.45 billion U.S. dollars) under management
around
the world.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted EquitiLink as saying that
the
widely-predicted increase in household savings this year is not
happening.
</P>
<P>
The July tax cuts, share giveaways and economic recession have
not
encouraged people to save more, EquitiLink said.
</P>
<P>
Savings declined one percent with 800 million NZ dollars wiped
off the
savings pool in the third quarter, taking the index down to
120.28, the
same level as a year ago, it added.
</P>
<P>
The index measures savings in both short- and long-term
financial
assets.
</P>
<P>
According to EquitiLink, the fall in the household pool of
savings
followed two quarters where savings remained static.
</P>
<P>
Savings in bank deposits rose 0.3 percent but the managed funds

sector fell by 2.5 percent, the sharpest drop in three years.
</P>
<P>
The appetite for borrowing continued, though at weaker levels
than
last year.
</P>
<P>
Household debt rose 1.12 percent, taking the household debt
indicator
to 138.65 during the third quarter, the lowest quarterly increase
for
three years.
</P>
<P>
The growth in borrowing has slowed in each of the past three
quarters.
Household debt rose 1.7 percent in the first quarter, and 1.5
percent in
the second quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Bank Rates at 30-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Retail deposit rates in New
Zealand have plunged to their lowest level in nearly three
decades, slashing returns for people with money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
According to data released last weekend by the Reserve Bank,
the central bank in the country, the average deposit rate on money
invested for six months fell to 4.15 percent in November, the
lowest since December 1970.
</P>
<P>
The central bank surveys banks each month and works out a
weighted average interest rate for deposits of at least 10,000 NZ
dollars (5,300 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On-call deposit rates have also tumbled. Banks in November were
 paying only 2.5 percent for money which could be withdrawn at any
time, about a third their level in June.
</P>
<P>
New Zealanders have 43 billion NZ dollars (22.8 billion U.S.
dollars) deposited in banks, compared to 55 billion NZ dollars
(29.2 billion U.S. dollars) of borrowings from banks, mainly in
the form of home mortgages.
</P>
<P>
However, savers earn more for money invested over three years,
a period over which banks pay an annual return of six percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
