<HEADLINE> Waste Processing Industry Attracts Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Investors are exhibiting
an increasing interest in participating in waste treatment ventures
in the south China city of Guangzhou and the government plans to
increase related assistance over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
A recent issue of the Guangdong-Hong Kong Information Daily
quoted officials from the Guangzhou Environmental Protection
Bureau as saying that the government plans to "completely
relinquish waste collection, transportation and processing to
market forces by the year 2010."
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that "the waste treatment sector requires
intensive high-tech expertise and will become the focus of
experts, professors and Ph.D. holders.
</P>
<P>
It noted that businesspeople from the United States
and Japan have invested in the city's waste treatment sector and a
number of projects are currently under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The major forms of cooperation center on joint ventures and
contracted projects.
</P>
<P>
Recycling waste yields power, diesel fuel, chemical fertilizers
and cement, in addition to helping clean the environment.
</P>
