<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Intends to Export Cement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is eyeing the markets
in Nepal and Bhutan to export its surplus production of cement,
The Daily Star newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"If everything goes well we shall be able to produce between
6.5 million and 7.0 million tons of cement by the year 2002 and
start exporting the surplus," A.K.M. Muhituddin, convener of
Bangladesh Cement Manufacturers Association, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has 13 cement factories at present, employing some
35,000 people and producing only 1.6 million tons of cement
against an annual capacity of 2.6 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The production can meet just 30 percent of the country's total
demands, with the rest to be imported. Power outrage and stiff
competition from foreign producers were hitting local producers,
Muhituddin said.
</P>
<P>
To satisfy the growing needs of the construction sector, which
contributed 6 percent to the country's gross domestic product
during the 1997-98 fiscal year, four joint venture plants with an
annual production capacity of 1.5 million tons would be set up and
would go into production by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
And the country's existing cement factories were being
modernized and expanded to raise their production capacity to 5.5
million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
The country was on its way to attain self-sufficiency in cement
by 2000 after the modernization was completed by the end of 1999,
Muhituddin added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0255 </DOCNO>
