<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Palm Oil Output Down 10 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's palm oil output
for this year dropped by 10 percent to 8.3 million tons from 9
million tons last year, according to Malaysian Primary Industries
Minister Lim Keng Yaik.
</P>
<P>
However, palm oil export value rose to 18 billion ringgit
(4.736 billion U.S. dollars) this year from 12.9 billion ringgit
(3.394 billion U.S. dollars) last year because of readjustments to
the ringgit against the U.S. dollar, Lim told a press conference
in Johor Baharu Sunday, the Malaysian news agency Bernama reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Attributing the output decline to the effects of the El Nino
and La Nina weather phenomena, Lim reminded small holders and
plantations not to compromise oil quality by picking premature oil
palm fruits because they wanted to capitalize on the current good
price of the commodity.
</P>
<P>
The minister advised the plantation sector to use part of the
returns from the current price boom to diversify investment,
including in production-boosting efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
