<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimmers to Have Upperhand in First-Day Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese swimmers, dispite one
ace unqualified, will notch up three to four golds from all the
five at stake in the first day's swimming competitions of the
Asian Games, a Chinese coach said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"According to their performances, our swimmers have the chance
to win three to four golds in this evening's finals," said coach
Guo Ruishan.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Given the swimmers' performances in the
preliminaries, Chinese swimmers have an edge in men's 100m
breaststroke, women's 400m individual medley and women's 100m
freestyle. If they brought out their best, they will take a gold
in either men's 200m freestyle or women's 4x200m freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
"But it's rather disappointing that my protege Du Jie failed to
qualify for the men's 200-meter freestyle finals," he added.
</P>
<P>
19-year-old Du, Chinese national titlist in 200m freestyle,
finished tenth with a dismal one minute 55.02 second.
</P>
<P>
"He is just too inexperienced and underestimated his
opponents," Guo said."
</P>
<P>
Du's teammate Wang Chuan finished second in 1:52.97 to qualify
comfortably for the finals. Torlarp Sethsothorn of Thailand came
in first in 1:52.77.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese swimmer Zeng Qiliang, the silver medallist of
men's 100m breaststroke in the world championships in January in
Perth, Australia, qualified first in 1:02.38 for the finals of his
specialty.
</P>
<P>
"He swam far better than his oppents, and the gold will surely
be his," said Guo.
</P>
<P>
Shan Ying, though qualified with a seventh finishing time of
58.32 in women's 100m freestyle preliminary, also has a chance to
carry all before her in the finals, said Guo.
</P>
<P>
"She was just too relaxed in the heat and didn't bring out her
best," Guo added.
</P>
<P>
Though world record holder Chen Yan and Wu Yanyan finished
third and fifth respectively in the women's 400m individual medley
preliminary, they will stave off the challenge from their Japanese
rivals to secure another gold for China in the finals, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
Yasuko Tajima and Miyuki Ishikawa, both from Japan, beat Chen
and Wu in the preliminary to finished top two respectively in
4:46.91 and 4:51.67.
</P>
<P>
Japanese swimming team leader Tsuyoshi Aoki sensed a tough
battle looming ahead in the first-day finals.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese swimmers reserved their energy in the
preliminaries for the evening's finals," he said through
interpretor.
</P>
<P>
"My swimmers will try their best in the finals to beat their
Chinese opponents," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
