<HEADLINE> Four Million Zimbabweans Need Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government needs
at least 120,000 tons of grain for the next three months to feed
more than four million people who have exhausted their food
reserves in communal areas countryside, the daily Herald reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
July Moyo, secretary for public service, labor and social
welfare ministry, told the newspaper Sunday that the number of
people registering for food aid was expected to grow as more
household stocks run out.
</P>
<P>
Some affected areas had already started receiving the relief
food, he said. Although the allocations were inadequate because
of the rising number of people requiring aid, this was all the
government would allocate every month.
</P>
<P>
According to the secretary, more than 500,000 people of the
over four million who have so far registered for food aid will
receive free food while the rest will get maize under the grain
loan scheme. They are expected to repay after the harvest.
</P>
<P>
Private transporters have been hired to supplement the efforts
of the state fleet to move the food as quickly as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
