<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharp Decline in Demand for Australian Wool Bottoms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Australia's semi-official wool
organization Woolmark Company Monday said the steep drop in demand
for Australia's wool overseas could be showing signs of an end.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly market briefing, Woolmark said the Asian crisis
was continuing to affect global demand for commodities but there
were signs of hope for raw wool.
</P>
<P>
Weak demand and competition for other fibers, such as cotton,
have been blamed for a sharp drop in both the export volume and
prices of Australian wool during the past several months.
</P>
<P>
The total wool export volumes of greasy wool for Australia, the
world's leading wool producer, had been pushed down 22 percent in
the four months to October, down from 259.8 million kg to 202.1
million kg.
</P>
<P>
The price of wool has also dropped with the value of wool
exports down 35 percent from 829 million U.S. dollars in the four
months to October, 1997 to 537 million U.S. dollars for the
corresponding period this year.
</P>
<P>
"There are, however, some signs that the sharp decline in raw
wool demand is bottoming out," Woolmark said.
</P>
<P>
China's raw wool demand picked up in October with Australian
exports to China, including Hong Kong, lifting by eight percent
compared with October 1997.
</P>
<P>
China buys about 25 percent of the wool Australia exports.
</P>
<P>
Some re-stocking of mills was taking place in China's Taiwan
and in South Korea while exports to these economies were up 68
percent and 33 percent in October, after 12 months of decline.
</P>
<P>
Exports to other markets including India, Turkey, Mexico and
the Czech Republic were also continuing to rise and expected to
increase even more when import duties were addressed, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
But Woolmark also noted that retail clothing sales had fallen
again in October in Japan and South Korea and that an excess
supply of clothing and uncertain domestic conditions were making
the retail market in China tougher.
</P>
<P>
Low consumer confidence also led to a drop of clothing sales in
many European countries, though retail conditions were better in
Italy than last year and could lead to improved sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
