<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Santo Domingo to Stage 2003 Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Santo Domingo, the capital
of the Dominican Republic, beat out Guadalajara, Mexico and
Medellin, Colombia on Sunday to be chosen as the host city for
the 2003 Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
Members of the general assembly of the Pan American Sports
Organization selected Santo Domingo in a second round of voting
after eliminating Medellin in the first round and Guadalajara in
the second. The vote count was not released.
</P>
<P>
Puello Herrera, president of the Dominican Olympic committee,
said the Dominican Republic, which suffered heavy damage from
Hurricane Georges in September, will be ready for 2003. It
already has repaired nearly 86 percent of the infrastructure
needed for the games, which will cost nearly 100 million U.S.
dollars to organize.
</P>
<P>
Puello Herrera attributed Sunday's victory to a strong
promotional campaign among the region's Olympic committees.
</P>
<P>
The 2003 games will mark the third time that a Caribbean
nation has been the host country. Previous hosts were Puerto Rico
and Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
