<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Democrats Confident of Surviving Censure Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's key democrats said
Monday they were confident that strong public trust would enable
the ruling Democratic Party to survive a censure motion by the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
"We were still more credible than the opposition in the eyes of
the public," Government spokesman Akapol Sorasuchart told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, led by the New Aspiration Party, threatened to
launch a censure motion against some government officials for
their support of the sixth letter of intent to the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The opposition maintained that the government had given up
Thailand's sovereignty to the IMF by accepting its conditions for
economic aid. Under the sixth letter of intent, the IMF will grant
Thailand 4.74 billion dollars as part of a bailout package
promised after the financial crisis broke out last year.
</P>
<P>
The debate is expected to be held in early January.
</P>
<P>
Akapol said the no-confidence debate would not change the
political scene and claimed that the opposition also knew it could
not bring the government down.
</P>
<P>
Opposition sources said the intended censure motion would not
target Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai because his popularity has
remained high.
</P>
<P>
Chalerm Yubamrung, a New Aspiration deputy leader, wanted the
debate to focus only on vulnerable ministers to show to the public
that the government had not been without flaws.
</P>
<P>
The opposition admitted earlier that they lacked sufficient
support in the parliament to topple the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
