<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Holds Women's Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A four-day conference on women
sponsored by the National Committee for Women's Affairs (NCWA)
began here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the first of its kind in Myanmar, aims to
promote the quality of life and ensure regular and sustainable
opportunities for women, safeguard the cultural heritage by women
and enhance their full participation in the nation-building
endeavor.
</P>
<P>
Attending the conference are delegates of the NCWA, government
departments and non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is carrying out a national action plan to speed up
efforts for improving women's condition in the country in line
with the Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action adopted at
the Fourth World Conference on Women held in Beijing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
After the Beijing conference, Myanmar formed the NCWA in 1996
to carry out the country's development project for women.
</P>
<P>
The NCWA has been able to adopt systematic plans and projects
for uplifting the role of women all over the country and success
has been reportedly achieved.
</P>
<P>
Of Myanmar's total population of 46.4 million in the 1997-98
fiscal year, 23.6 million or 50.34 percent are women, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
A census conducted in 1994 showed that 46 percent of Myanmar
women above the age of 10 were in the labor force in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the national literacy rate of women has gone up to
71.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Opposes EU Demand on Closing Sole Nuclear Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has voiced opposition to
European Union's demand for closing of Bulgaria's sole nuclear
plant on grounds of environmental protection, Bulgarian National
Radio said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the EU's demand put forward at a meeting in
Brussels on December 2, Krassimir Nikolov, chief of the Kozlodoui
plant on the Danube, said the plant is among the best in Europe
and worldwide in nuclear safety.
</P>
<P>
"The closing of the Kozlodoui Nuclear plant, which generates
some 40 percent of the country's electricity, is now out of the
question, " Nikolov stressed, adding that the closure would
greatly undermine the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
The EU's demand was raised under an EU-Bulgaria agreement in
1993 that the first four of a total of six reactors at the
Kozlodoui's should be closed before the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
After signing of the agreement, however, Bulgaria has been
holding that the nuclear safety has been completely improved
thanks to renewal of the installations in the plant.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Roumen Ovcharov, legislator of the opposition
Bulgarian Socialist Party and former energy minister said closing
the reactors would also deal a blow at the nation's security. He
called on all the statesmen and politicians to rally behind a
single position to protect the nation's interests.
</P>
<P>
Mihail Shishenkov, head of the plant's Central Laboratory for
Radiological Control, told the same radio that the readings taken
by the Laboratory and other monitoring entities showed no elevated
radiation were above the usual levels.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the International Atomic Energy Agency will arrive
at Kozlodoui next month at the invitation of the Bulgarian
government to inspect the operation of the plant, Nikolov said.
</P>
<P>
According to the strategy of the Committee for Use of Atomic
Energy for Peaceful Purposes, Kozlodoui's oldest two reactors, the
440 MW Unit One and Unit Two, are to be decommissioned in the
first decade of next century, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0280 </DOCNO>
