<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Hopes for One Medal in Track and Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Asiad delegation of Hong
Kong, China hopes to win a medal in the track and field
competitions at the Asian Games, head coach Tian Haijiang said
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tian said that Hong Kong's athletes have maintained a good form
after arriving at Bangkok and are ready to run.
</P>
<P>
"We have a good chance to win a medal, and winning a medal of
any color would be a breakthrough," Tian said.
</P>
<P>
"The arch-rival is ourselves," Tian said. "We should have the
confidence."
</P>
<P>
The biggest athletics medal hopeful for Hong Kong, competing in
its first Asian Games after returning to the embrace of China in
July 1, 1997, is women's 100 meters hurdler Chan Sau Ying, who
will run her fourth and perhaps last Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Chan, who has a personal best time of 13.06 seconds, said she
still believe the best time is right ahead after coming fourth
twice in the Beijing and Hiroshima Games.
</P>
<P>
"I will try my best," she said. "If everything goes right, I
can win a medal."
</P>
<P>
A total of 16 Hong Kong athletes will take part in nine events
of the track and field competition in the Games.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Bangkok, they held a training camp in Guangxi
Autonomous Region in south China with their mainland counterparts
for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We have made a remarkable improvement since there are quite a
few Asia's best athletes in the Chinese national team," Tian said.
</P>
<P>
The track and field competitions of the Asian Games will be
held from December 13 to 20, and China is expected to win a lion's
share of gold medals. 
</P>
