<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. At Odds Over Thai Official For WTO Top Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- United States government
agencies are bickering over whether to support Thai Deputy Prime
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi's bid to become the new chief of
the World Trade Organization (WTO), the Bangkok Post reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decision is considered crucial to the selection of the
WTO chief, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to internal government disagreements, there are two
factors holding up the decision by the United States on whether to
support Supachai or former New Zealand prime minister Michael
Moore, two major contenders for the post, the paper quoted
diplomatic sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
One stumbling block is that American officials want to see
where the votes of a wavering European Union will go.
</P>
<P>
The EU remained badly split as late as Sunday, roughly along
north-south lines -- with many northern Europeans including
Scandinavians in favor of Supachai.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been unable to make a choice despite several rounds
of discussions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Treasury Department has pressed President Bill Clinton
to back Supachai, but Trade Representative Charlene Barshevsky
Favors Moore.
</P>
<P>
Another delaying factor is that Washington is determined to get
one of the deputy-director seats.
</P>
<P>
"The US wants to be a deputy director so badly it probably will
vote for anyone who offers them the position," one source was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said it was premature to speculate that WTO members
will have to vote on the next director. Regulations of the world
trading body require consensus. Except in dire circumstances,
these rules are unlikely to be waived.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a vote might leave the winner beholden only to the
countries which supported him. If a meeting scheduled for Friday
fails again to choose a new chief, nations will consider holding a
vote next month, as suggested by Egypt and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
There are another two contenders vying for the post -- former
trade minister Roy MacLaren of Canada and former agricultural
minister Hassan Abouyoub of Morocco. But diplomatic sources said
the contest is essentially a two-man race between Supachai and the
New Zealander. The Thai Candidate has more votes as of today, but
the U.S. and European votes are so crucial that victory is far
from assured for Supachai.
</P>
<P>
The WTO is supposed to replace its first director Renato
Ruggiero of Italy, by April at the latest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech International Payment Deficit Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 6 (Xinhua) -- During the first three quarters
of this year the Czech Republic's deficit of international payment
dropped sharply to 15.9 billion korunas (around 530 million
U.S. dollars), or one-fifth of the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Pavel Palivec, spokesman for the Czech State Bank, attributed
this record decline in years to the active development of foreign
trade, sharp reduction of foreign trade deficit and the increase
of tourism.
</P>
<P>
The adverse balance of international payment was as high as
79.4 billion korunas (about 2.65 billion dollars) in the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
This positive development comes after years of worsening
balance of international payment. In 1997, the adverse balance
hit 65.8 billion korunas (about 2.19 billion dollars), or 6.5
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) exceeding the
generally recognized alert level.
</P>
<P>
This index shrank to 1.8 percent in the first half of this year
and is expected to go down to 1.5 percent for the whole year of
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
