<HEADLINE> Nepali Children Administered Polio Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- About 3.8 million Nepalese
children aged under five are being administered polio drops Monday
for the third consecutive year as the government resolves to
eradicate the disease from the country by 2000.
</P>
<P>
They are scheduled to be vaccinated free of charge again on
January 18, 1999.
</P>
<P>
A total of 23,000 vaccination centers have been set up
throughout the country and some 100,000 volunteers mobilized for
the immunization program, Health Minister K.B. Gurung said in a
statement, adding that the programs in the past two years were
successful.
</P>
<P>
The government has declared the two days holidays for all
government offices and schools except the ministries and
central-level departments.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Japanese government, a number of
international agencies including the World Health Organization and
the United Nations Children's Fund are supporting the government's
efforts to eradicate polio, a disease which cripples children.
</P>
