<HEADLINE> Thailand to Amend Reform Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai government officials
reiterated on Monday that they would amend the country's
controversial economic reform bills to make sure they benefit
Thais.
</P>
<P>
The bills, which went into effect soon after the financial
crisis broke out last year, allows foreigners to buy Thai assets
and own larger shares of properties.
</P>
<P>
Thai activists are campaigning against the bills, saying they
will open up the country to foreign investors who will take over
Thai jobs and assets.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister's Office Minister Abhisit Vejjajiva told
reporters that the alien business, bankruptcy and foreclosure
bills might be changed, but he refused to give details.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would look at the social and legal
impact of the measures before any changes could be made.
</P>
<P>
"The government will have to listen to its critics and agree to
some changes, provided they do not upset the main goal of the
economic measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident that foreign investors would
understand if some details were altered.
</P>
<P>
"They have to understand and be realistic. I don't remember a
country going through the economic reform process without someone
opposing it," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Investors could rest assured that the government was determined
to push through reforms as soon as possible, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
