<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Bulgarians Anxious at Year's End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A poll conducted by the National
Public Opinion Center shows there is a relatively high level of
anxiety among ordinary Bulgarians, the Bulgarian news agency
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
When asked "how do you assess the situation in the country
now?" 40 percent answered "somewhat strained," 16 percent
"troubled," and 40 percent "calm."
</P>
<P>
Poverty and unemployment weigh high on the mind of nearly one
in four of the interviewees, shows the poll which was conducted in
October.
</P>
<P>
Disapproval rate of the government's action to cope with
unemployment and to boost income is slightly weaker than four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
Merely 16 percent of the respondents find that the reforms are
making successful progress, 22 percent think the reforms are
failing, and 33 percent believe the reforms have stagnated.
</P>
<P>
To the question "did you go on holiday this summer?" 47 percent
were negative "because I couldn't afford it."
</P>
<P>
For lack of money, 77 percent will deny themselves the usual
variety of foods, 63 percent the usual quantity of food, 36
percent medicines, 54 percent the purchase of newspapers and
magazines, and 57 percent the purchase of books, the poll shows.
</P>
<P>
In the search for ways to cope with these problems, fewer opt
for working harder (48 percent in July 1997 and 47 percent in the
poll), or for a new job (12 percent in July 1997 and 4 percent
the poll).
</P>
<P>
However, the pollsters say the Bulgarians have not given up working
more, but simply have realized that extra work is not a good
enough way of handling economic hardship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
