<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Libraries Help Boost Literacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's libraries in 304
townships are playing an important role in boosting the country's
literacy, supported by an average annual publication of over 3,000
titles of books on science, industry and technology.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is also implementing a national plan of action for
education for all. The plan, laid down by the World Education
Conference on Education for All held in Thailand in 1990, covers
both formal and non-formal education.
</P>
<P>
The formal education is designed to enable school-age children
from five to nine to go to school and primary school children to
complete primary education.
</P>
<P>
Non-formal education is aimed at enabling illiterates over
school age (over 15) to become literate by means of the
"functional literacy program."
</P>
<P>
The two education programs aim to ensure that 80 percent of the
population complete primary education, and to reduce the adult
illiteracy rate from 22 percent to 11 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's literacy campaign started in 1964. The illiteracy
rate was reduced by half to 21 percent in 1983 from 43 percent in
1963.
</P>
<P>
Between 1964 and 1988, 490,398 volunteers took part in literacy
activities with more than 2.4 million illiterates becoming
literate.
</P>
<P>
The national literacy rate of Myanmar has now gone up to 87.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar was awarded two international prizes for its successful
 literacy activities by the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization -- the Mahammad Reza Pahlavi Literacy
Prize in 1971 and the Noma Prize in 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
