<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Upgrades Its 747 Production System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Boeing and its partners have
quietly invested about 350 million U.S. dollars to upgrade the 747
production system, according to Sunday's Seattle Times.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted "insiders" as saying that the investment in
new tooling and design procedures is intended to protect Boeing's only
monopoly franchise -- the 747 jumbo jet, the most profitable plane in
Boeing's production line.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's investment decision was made when it prepares for massive
layoffs and a contraction of its commercial airplane operation.
</P>
<P>
With the money, the Seattle-based aircraft manufacturer is
overhauling aging tooling and introducing a digital-design process.
The upgraded production system is supposed to make Boeing's oldest and
most famous plane more competitive by reducing costly "rework" and
thus cutting the number of people working on it as well as the price,
which is listed at 160 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The overhaul will also open the door to new 747 derivative models,
either with more seats or flying longer distance, that could steal
market share from rival Airbus.
</P>
<P>
Competing head-to-head with 747, Airbus plans to launch A3XX, a
four-engine, 550-seat "superjumbo" jet next year.
</P>
<P>
But Boeing's big investment on 747 is also a risky one. Only last
week, sagging Asian demand for jumbo airplanes forced the company to
dramatically cut the 747 production rate to two, and perhaps even to
one, aircraft a month by 2000, down from five a month today.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Boeing faces shrinking long-term demand for its 440-seat
four-engine planes because airlines are increasingly favoring the
large twin-engine jet with fewer seats, which are more fuel-efficient
and easier to maintain and operate.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, both Boeing and Airbus eye the future market for
large airplanes. Over the next 20 years, Boeing estimates airline
traffic will grow nearly five percent annually and airlines will need
1,030 jumbo-size airplanes. Airbus estimates airlines will need more
than 1,300 planes larger than 747. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
