<HEADLINE> Northeastern Chinese Province Getting More Foreign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a heavy
industrial center in northeast China, is still attractive to
foreign investors and its contracts on foreign investment were up
0.6 percent to 3.67 billion U.S. dollars worth in the first ten
months this year.
</P>
<P>
The increased investment is in contrast with the drop of 1.2
percent in the number of foreign-invested projects approved,
which is 1,370, according to the provincial foreign trade and
economic cooperation department.
</P>
<P>
The province used 670 million U.S. dollars worth of foreign
loans in the ten months, up 22 percent on an annual basis. Its
7,322 foreign-backed enterprises exported 2.82 billion
U.S. dollars worth of goods in the same period, an increase of
17.5 percent. Their industrial output value rose by a yearly rate
of 11 percent to 56.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Department officials said that the increased foreign investment
comes in spite of the Asian financial crisis mainly because of
Europe and North America's increased funding, which has more than
offset the reduction in investment from Southeast Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
