<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines to Submit Rehabilitation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The financially-troubled
Philippine Airlines (PAL) is taking its first shaky step towards
recovery as it will submit a proposed rehabilitation plan to the
country's Securities and Exchange Commission Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Business World newspaper reported Monday that PAL is making
its move amid speculation about whether or not Cathay Pacific
Airways would return to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, President Joseph Estrada said he would do
everything he could to convince the two parties to resume their
talks over a possible merge, by which Cathay would buy a
substantial stake into PAL.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the rehabilitation plan outlines the flag
carrier's business program for the next five years with the goal
of generating revenues of about 855 million U.S. dollars by the
year 2003.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, PAL hopes to reach its target revenue with a
fleet of 22 aircraft and a manpower complement of around 7,500
employees, 500 less than its current 8,000-strong work force, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The plan also provides for the improvement of PAL's
international route network as well as how to take better
advantage of the flag carrier's current 63 percent share of the
Philippine aviation market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
