<HEADLINE> Investments in Infrastructure to Grow Quickly: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said that investments in infrastructure projects for local
government units in the Asia Pacific region would reach around 292
billion U.S. dollars by the year 2020 from 38 billion dollars in
1990.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Bulletin newspaper Monday quoted Asad Ali Shah, ADB
manager for water supply, as saying that 30 percent of the total
investments would account for the development of water supply.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is looking at areas which it could help finance
infrastructure projects such as water supply, urban sector
support, low-cost housing and financing, the ADB official said.
</P>
<P>
Shah said that one important challenge facing the ADB is the
institutional and capacity building programs of municipal
governments to source funding requirements.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the development is fully-entrenched in municipal
governments, sustained growth would not be achieved," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, he said, the ADB plans to extend loans
amounting to 200 million to the Philippines for its regional
development projects and the reduction of level of poverty in
urban centers. 
