<HEADLINE> Arresting Cultural Relics Thieves In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Police in China's Hubei Province
have successfully stopped a burglary that involved priceless
cultural relics at the Taoist Wudang Mountain.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that one of the suspects were caught on the
scene, the stolen articles have been recovered and are all in safe
keeping now, and the investigation is still underway.
</P>
<P>
In late November, Zhang Zhongyu, a farmer in Magang County,
took a train to Wudang Mountain, which is known for its scenery
and its significance for Taoism. with another villager, Xiao
Youliang.
</P>
<P>
Disguised as tourists, the two visited temples and halls where
cultural relics were in display. Around midnight on the 25th, they
brought tools and slipped into Tai Shan Temple where they pried
open a locked door on the main palace and took away seven pieces
of cultural relics, four of which were on the state's top
protection list.
</P>
<P>
As they tried to leave the scene with the stolen articles,
guards on patrol discovered them and in the pursuit, Zhang was
captured, but Xiao escaped.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
