<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Border Trade Increases In Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Huang Shizeng, a Chinese farmer
who lives on the border of south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region with Vietnam, says he can still remember the
first deal he made with Vietnamese from across the border.
</P>
<P>
"I was spraying pesticide in the field when I looked up and saw
a few Vietnamese in rags sneaking up to me. They wanted to trade
my thermoses and electric torches with the products they had in
hand," he recalls.
</P>
<P>
This exchange of goods was the beginning of the border
trade with Vietnam. The village of Miqi, where Huang lives, has 30
households. The border runs through the village to its south. Huang
pointed to a deserted trading street and said it was crowded and
busy between 1989 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
Chen Zhongle, an official in the city of Pingxiang, under whose
jurisdiction Miqi is, says that the China-Vietnam border trade was
initially done mainly on this street. Then it started to take on
more modern features like joint operations and technological
cooperation, with full government support.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the autonomous regional government isssued
preferential trade policies for border areas to promote economic
exchanges with Vietnam. Traders did not have to pay import tariffs
if they bought something for less than 1,000 yuan at the trading
centers and tariffs were cut by half for small volumes of
imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Border Trade In Guangxi (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The autonomous region has a 1,020-km border and opened 25
border markets in the last two decades. The market at Miqi was
deserted because of transport difficulties. Other counties with
good transportation prospered.
</P>
<P>
Exports from China are mainly machinery, building materials,
spayers, pesticides, bicycles, electric fans, sewing
machines, beer, textiles and thermoses.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's exports are mainly fruits, lumber, marine products
rubber and minerals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese exports do well in Vietnam, because they are cheap and
have reasonably quality, and, more important, they are in
short supply in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi's border trade is worth 3.1 billion yuan annually, up
from 450 million yuan in 1989.
</P>
<P>
According to the government of Pingxiang, 13,000 of its 170,000
people are involved in border trade. This has affected the growth
of other sectors like tourism, transportation, warehousing, and
the food service industry. Per capita income of farmers here
increased from 551 yuan 9 years ago to the present 2,173
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981207.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Becomes High-Tech Exporter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shenzhen nearby
Hong Kong has transformed itself from Hong Kong's major fresh
vegetable and meat provider to a machinery and electronics
products exporter in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official of the city government,
machinery and electronics exports accounted for nearly 60 percent
of the city's total exports last year.
</P>
<P>
This is attributable to the presence of large multinationals
like IBM, Hitachi and Fuji, said Li Qingsen, director of the
city's foreign investment bureau.
</P>
<P>
There are 150 multinationals, 36 from the world's top 500, with
investments in this former fishing village, and foreign investors
contributed 36 percent of the city's GDP last year, Li said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of October, Shenzhen had used 16.91 billion
U.S. dollars worth of foreign investment, which is earmarked for
more than 15,000 projects.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 51 Sino-foreign joint ventures in the city were
among the country's top 500 businesses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
