<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Gets Two-Day Impeachment Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The White House will have 30
hours over two days to present its defense of U.S. President Bill
Clinton but the House of Representatives Judiciary Committee made
clear Sunday it would not be deterred from starting the
impeachment debate this week.
</P>
<P>
White House lawyers had asked for three to four days to make
its case, but the Judiciary Committee countered Sunday with an
offer of two 15-hour days on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The committee plans to start the impeachment debate on
Thursday, and it will continue into Friday.
</P>
<P>
Given the public statements of committee members, it is all but
certain the panel will vote at least one article of impeachment
arising from the Monica Lewinsky matter, and the full House will
take it up the week of December 14.
</P>
<P>
In a testy letter, Judiciary chief of staff and general counsel
Thomas Mooney said the White House can have some time but
Judiciary Committee members will be able to question any of the
witnesses Clinton's lawyers present.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Committee who are conducting the
impeachment inquiry will be permitted to ask questions of anyone
who appears before the Committee," Mooney wrote in a letter
released to reporters.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said the president's team
would formally respond on Monday, but would work within the
framework. 
</P>
</TEXT>
